{"title_page": "Vision (Marvel Comics)", "text_new": "{{short description|fictional superhero appearing in Marvel Comics}}\n{{About|the character introduced in Avengers #57|all Visions by Marvel Comics|Vision (comics)}}\n\n{{Infobox comics character<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image=[[File:Avengers Vol 4 24.1.jpg|250px|alt=]]\n|caption='''Vision''' on the cover of ''[[The Avengers (comic book)|Avengers]]'' #24.1 (March 2012).<br>Art by [[Brandon Peterson]].\n|character_name=Vision\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''[[The Avengers (comic book)|The Avengers]]'' #57 (October 1968)\n|creators=[[Roy Thomas]]<br />[[Stan Lee]]<br>[[John Buscema]]\n|homeworld=[[Brooklyn, New York]]\n|alliances=[[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]<br />[[West Coast Avengers]]<br />[[Avengers A.I.]]<br />[[Defenders (comics)|Defenders]]<br>[[The Mighty Avengers|Mighty Avengers]]<br>[[The New Avengers (comics)|New Avengers]]\n|aliases=Victor Shade\n|partners=[[Scarlet Witch]]\n|powers=\n* Superhuman agility, intelligence, strength and speed\n* Flight\n* Density control\n* Intangibility\n* Mass manipulation\n* Regeneration\n* Solar energy projection\n* Technopathy\n}}\n\n'''Vision''' is a fictional [[superhero]] appearing in [[American comic book]]s published by [[Marvel Comics]]. He is an [[Android (robot)|android]] and a member of the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]] who first appeared in ''[[The Avengers (comic)|The Avengers]]'' #57 (October 1968). He is loosely based on the [[Timely Comics]] [[Vision (Timely Comics)|character of the same name]].\n\n[[Paul Bettany]] portrays the character in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] films ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015), ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' (2016), and ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' (2018). Bettany will be reprising the role in the [[Disney+]] upcoming series ''[[WandaVision]]'' (2020).\n\n== Publication history ==\nEditor [[Stan Lee]] and writer [[Roy Thomas]] decided to add a new team member to the superhero-team series ''[[The Avengers (comic book)|The Avengers]]''. Thomas wanted to bring back the Golden Age [[Vision (Aarkus)]] but Lee was set on introducing an android member. Thomas ultimately compromised by using a new, android Vision.<ref name=\"back45\">{{cite journal|last= Walker|first= Karen|date= December 2010|title= Shattered Dreams: Vision and the Scarlet Witch|journal= [[Back Issue!]]|issue= 45|pages= 59\u201365| publisher= [[TwoMorrows Publishing]]}}</ref> The second Vision [[first appearance|first appeared]] in ''The Avengers'' #57 (Oct. 1968). Thomas wanted the character to be white as befitting his ghostly name, but printing limitations of the time would have rendered him colorless, with un-inked paper where his skin should be. He settled on red as he did not want Vision to be green like the [[Hulk]] or blue like the [[Homo mermanus|Atlanteans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/age-ultron-creator-roy-thomas-791320|title=Marvel Legend Reveals What Stan Lee Initially \"Hated\" About 'Age of Ultron' Breakout|publisher=}}</ref> The character has been compared with [[Spock]] from ''[[Star Trek]]'', but Thomas said that he was barely aware of the TV series at the time.<ref name=\"oral\">{{cite web |url= https://www.yahoo.com/movies/the-secret-origins-of-vision-and-ultron-an-oral-118171812977.html|title= The Secret Origins of Vision and Ultron: An Oral History|author=Marcus Errico|date= May 6, 2015|publisher= Yahoo|accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref> He acknowledged being influenced by the [[Adam Link]] character by [[Otto Binder]], one of the first robots treated as a sympathetic character rather than as a mechanical tool.<ref name=\"oral\" />\n\nIn ''The Avengers'' #75 (April 1970), the [[Scarlet Witch]] is reintroduced to the team and soon becomes a love interest for Vision. Thomas recounted, \"I felt that a romance of some sort would help the character development in ''The Avengers'', and the Vision was a prime candidate because he appeared only in that mag... as did Wanda, for that matter. So they became a pair, for just such practical considerations. It would also, I felt, add to the development I was doing on the Vision's attempting to become \u2018human.\u2019\"<ref name=\"back45\" /> Thomas also came up with the idea of the Vision having been created from the body of the [[Human Torch (android)|Human Torch]], but only planted a vague clue to this (in ''The Avengers'' #93) before leaving the series. It was finally followed up in ''The Avengers'' #134\u2013135. Writer [[Steve Englehart]] explained, \"That plot was well known in-house for years, and since Roy [Thomas] and [[Neal Adams|Neal [Adams]]] hadn't had a chance to do it, I did it on my watch with Roy's blessing.\"<ref name=\"Back38\">{{cite journal|last= Walker|first= Karen|date= February 2010|title= Ultron: The Black Sheep of the Avengers Family|journal= Back Issue!|issue= 38|page= 25|publisher= TwoMorrows Publishing}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972 Vision appeared with [[Spider-Man]] in ''[[Marvel Team-Up]]'' #5, \"A Passion of the Mind\", in which a giant robot scout from [[the Kree-Skrull War]] is found to be interfering with Vision's brain waves.\n\nVision and Scarlet Witch were married in ''Giant-Size Avengers'' #4 (June 1975). The couple starred in the [[Limited series (comics)|limited series]] ''[[The Vision and the Scarlet Witch]]'' #1\u20134 (Nov. 1982 \u2013 Feb. 1983), by writer [[Bill Mantlo]] and [[penciller]] [[Rick Leonardi]]. This was followed by a second volume numbered #1\u201312 (Oct. 1985 \u2013 Sept. 1986), written by Steve Englehart and penciled by [[Richard Howell (comics)|Richard Howell]], in which the Scarlet Witch gives birth to twin boys conceived with Vision through magical means.\n\nThe \"Vision Quest\" story in ''[[West Coast Avengers]]'' #42\u201345 (March \u2013 June 1989) by writer/penciller [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] took the character away from his earlier depictions as a \"synthetic human\" and emphasized his android nature. The story had the Vision's memory and human brain patterns wiped out, severed his relationship with his wife, revealed their children to be essentially imaginary constructs, and included a two-page spread showing a dismantled Vision. Journalist Karen Walker later commented, \"This image alone has probably done more to shape how future writers (and readers) perceive the character than anything before or since. Once seen broken down into component parts, it's hard to truly move past that image and think of Vision as a synthetic man, not a machine.\"<ref name=\"back45\" />\n\nVision appeared in a solo limited series, ''Vision'', #1\u20134 (Nov. 1994 \u2013 Feb. 1995), by writer [[Bob Harras]] and penciller Manny Clark. Nearly a decade after that came a second four-issue volume (Oct. 2002 \u2013 Jan. 2003), written by [[Geoff Johns]] and penciled by [[Ivan Reis]].\n\nThe series ''[[Young Avengers]]'', which ran 12 issues from April 2005 to August 2006, introduced [[Vision (Jonas)|a new Vision]], who is a combination of the synthezoid Vision's program files and the armor and mental engrams of the hero [[Iron Lad]].\n\nVision appeared as a regular character in the 2010\u20132013 ''Avengers'' series, from issue #19 (January 2012) through its final issue #34 (January 2013).\n\nVision again appeared in a solo series, ''Vision'', with #1 that started in November 2015 and ended with #12 in October 2016.\n\n== Fictional character biography ==\n[[File:Avengers57.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Debut of the [[Silver Age of comic books|Silver Age]] Vision: ''[[Avengers (comics)|The Avengers]]'' #57 (Oct. 1968). Cover pencils by [[John Buscema]].<ref>Cover inker Buscema per [http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=22241 Grand Comics Database: ''The Avengers'' #57], or [[George Klein (comics)|George Klein]] per ''The Official Marvel Index to The Avengers'' #3 (Oct. 1987), Marvel Comics.</ref>]]\n\nThe robot [[Ultron]] is the creator of Vision, a type of [[Android (robot)|android]] he calls a \"synthezoid\", for use against Ultron's own creator, Dr. [[Hank Pym]] (Ant-Man/Giant Man/Goliath/Yellowjacket) and Pym's wife, Janet van Dyne (the [[Wasp (comics)|Wasp]]) of the superhero team the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]. Ultron sends his new servant to lead the Avengers into a trap. Wasp is the first to encounter the synthezoid, and describes it as a \"vision\" while trying to escape. Adopting the name, Vision is convinced by the Avengers to turn against Ultron.<ref>''Avengers'' #57 (Oct. 1968). Marvel Comics.</ref> After learning how Ultron created him, using the brain patterns of then-deceased Simon Williams ([[Wonder Man]]), Vision becomes a member of the team.<ref>''Avengers'' #58. Marvel Comics.</ref> The team initially believes the Vision's body was created from that of the android [[Human Torch (android)|original Human Torch]].<ref>Hinted at in ''The Avengers'' #116 & 118 (Oct. & Dec. 1973). Marvel Comics.</ref> The Avengers later are told that the time lord [[Immortus]] used the power of the Forever Crystal to split the original Human Torch into two entities \u2013 one body remained the original Torch while Ultron rebuilt the other as the Vision. This was part of his plan to nurture a relationship for the Scarlet Witch that would prevent her from having any children, as her power level meant that any offspring she might have could threaten the cosmic beings of the Marvel Universe.<ref>''Avengers Forever'' #8 (July 1999). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nNot long after joining the team, Vision is temporarily controlled by Ultron, and rebuilds Ultron out of adamantium, battling the Avengers before regaining control of himself.<ref>''Avengers'' #66\u201368. Marvel Comics.</ref> Shortly after that, the Vision first meets Wanda Maximoff, the [[Mutant (Marvel Comics)|mutant]] [[Scarlet Witch]],<ref>''Avengers'' #76. Marvel Comics.</ref> with whom he later becomes romantically involved.<ref>''Avengers'' #108\u2013109. Marvel Comics.</ref> The two eventually marry and, via the Scarlet Witch's hex powers, they have twin boys named Thomas and William.<ref>''Vision and the Scarlet Witch'' vol. 2, #3 & 12 (Dec. 1985 & Sept. 1986). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nWhen Vision attempts to penetrate an energy field erected by the villain [[Annihilus]], he \"shuts down\",<ref>''The Avengers'' #233 (July 1983). Marvel Comics.</ref> and even after regaining consciousness weeks later,<ref>''Avengers'' #238 (Nov. 1983). Marvel Comics.</ref> remains paralyzed and assumes a [[Holography|holographic]] form. He eventually regains control of his body and becomes team leader.<ref>''Avengers'' #242\u2013243 (April \u2013 May 1984). Marvel Comics.</ref> Having become unbalanced by these events, he attempts to take control of the world's computers.<ref>''Avengers'' #251 (Jan. 1985). Marvel Comics.</ref> With the aid of the Avengers, Vision is restored to his normal self, but now closely monitored by a coalition of governments.<ref>''Avengers'' #253\u2013254 (March\u2013April 1984). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nIn the \"Vision Quest\" storyline, rogue agents of the [[United States]] government, manipulated by the [[time travel]]er [[Immortus]], abduct the Vision and dismantle him. The Avengers recover the parts, and Dr. Pym rebuilds Vision, but with a chalk-white complexion. However, the revived Simon Williams does not allow his brain patterns to be used again to provide a matrix for Vision's emotions, explaining that the original process, done without his consent, had \"ripped out his soul\". This, along with damage to Vision's synthetic skin when he was dismantled, results in the synthezoid's resurrection as a colorless and emotionless [[Android (robot)|artificial human]].<ref>''West Coast Avengers'' #42\u201344 (March\u2013May 1989). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Torch (android)|original Human Torch]] also returns from his own apparent demise, casting doubt on Vision's identity. Vision and the Scarlet Witch's children are then revealed to be fragments of the soul of the [[demon]] [[Mephisto (comics)|Mephisto]], who had been broken apart by [[Franklin Richards (Fantastic Four)|Franklin Richards]] shortly before the birth of the twins. The twins are absorbed back into Mephisto, which temporarily drives Wanda insane. Although she recovers, Wanda and Vision separate, each operating on a different Avengers team.<ref>''Avengers West Coast'' #51\u201352 (Nov.-Dec. 1989). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nVision gradually regains his emotions, by adopting new brain patterns from deceased scientist Alex Lipton,<ref>''Avengers Spotlight'', #40 (Jan. 1990). Marvel Comics.</ref> and gains a new body that resembles his original. In addition, Simon Williams' brain patterns gradually reemerge and meld with Lipton's patterns, restoring Vision's full capacity for emotion.<ref>''Vision'', #1\u20134 (Nov. 1994 \u2013 Feb. 1995), Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nShortly after a reformation of the Avengers, Vision sustains massive damage in the final battle with the sorceress [[Morgan le Fay (Marvel Comics)|Morgan Le Fey]],<ref>''Avengers'' vol. 3, #4 (May 1998). Marvel Comics.</ref> and although incapacitated for several weeks, is eventually rebuilt and recovers.<ref>''Avengers'' vol. 3, #12 (Jan. 1999). Marvel Comics.</ref> While recovering, Vision gives up his attempt to reconcile with his wife, although he is revealed to retain a fondness for her culture, such as visiting a restaurant that specifically caters to Wanda's childhood community simply because he enjoys the ambience. Remaining a member of the Avengers, he briefly becomes romantically involved with teammates [[Ms. Marvel|Carol Danvers]] (a.k.a. Warbird/Ms. Marvel) and [[Mantis (Marvel Comics)|Mantis]] before attempting again to reconcile with the Scarlet Witch.\n\n=== Disassembled / Reassembled ===\nGrief over the loss of the twins, however, drives Wanda insane again, and she attempts to alter reality to recreate them. This causes a series of catastrophic events that includes Vision crashing an Avengers [[List of vehicles in Marvel Comics#Quinjet|Quinjet]] into [[Avengers Mansion]]. The Vision advises his teammates that he is no longer in control of his body, and then expels several spheres that form into five Ultrons. The Avengers destroy them, and an enraged [[She-Hulk]] tears apart the remains of the Vision, having been driven to a breaking point by the rapid slew of attacks against the Avengers. The Avengers later believed that [[Ultron]] may have put a command in the Vision that would have been activated by the Avengers' Code White alert during one of the many periods in which Vision was held prisoner by Ultron, though it was later revealed that Dr. Doom forced Scarlet Witch to send Vision against her teammates.<ref name=\"avengersdisassembled\">''The Avengers'' #500 (Sept. 2004). Marvel Comics.</ref><ref>name=\"avengersthechildren'scrusade\">''Avengers The Children's Crusade''(2010). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nVision's operating system and program files are later used in the creation of Iron Lad's armor, which becomes [[Vision (Jonas)|a sentient being of its own]]. In ''Mighty Avengers'' the original Vision and Iron Lad are briefly separated from this being by the power of the Cosmic Cube.<ref>'' The Mighty Avengers'' #33 (Jan. 2010). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring the \"[[Chaos War (comics)|Chaos War]]\" story line, Vision is one of many deceased heroes restored to life after the events in the death realms.<ref>''Chaos War: Dead Avengers'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> Vision joins with the other resurrected Avengers in their fight against Grim Reaper and Nekra.<ref>''Chaos War: Dead Avengers'' #2. Marvel Comics.</ref> During the fight, Vision blows himself up while in battle with Grim Reaper, killing them both.<ref>''Chaos War: Dead Avengers'' #3. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nFollowing the \"[[Fear Itself (comics)|Fear Itself]]\" story line, Tony Stark is able to rebuild Vision, who once again joins the Avengers.<ref>''Avengers'' Vol. 4 #19 (Jan. 2012). Marvel Comics.</ref> After being informed about what happened after his destruction, the Vision sees She-Hulk, telling her he does not blame her for what happened. He then goes to Utopia to confront [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Magneto]], threatening Magneto to tell him where Wanda is. Magneto uses his powers to subdue the Vision but spares him, saying he believes Wanda still cares for the Vision and that Magneto does not want to hurt her more. Captain America talks to the Vision afterward, telling him he needs to move forward.<ref>''Avengers'' Vol. 4 #24.1 (May 2012). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring a subsequent confrontation with the returned Wanda at the start of the \"[[Avengers vs. X-Men]]\" story line, Vision claims that her use of his body to attack his friends is something that he cannot forgive and, while he banishes her from the mansion, he also sheds tears after her departure.<ref>''Avengers vs. X-Men'' #0 (May 2012). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring the ''[[Marvel NOW!]]'' relaunch, Vision leaves the Avengers in order to find himself following a battle with [[Sunturion]]. After departing the team, he is shown visiting [[Wiccan (comics)|Billy Kaplan]], the teenage reincarnation of one of his sons.<ref>''Avengers Assemble Annual'' #1 (February 2013). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nFollowing the \"[[Age of Ultron]]\" storyline, Vision joins Hank Pym's [[Avengers A.I.]] alongside [[Monica Chang]], [[Victor Mancha]], and a reprogrammed [[Doombot]].<ref>''Avengers A.I.'' #1, Marvel Comics.</ref> He also upgraded himself and is now actually composed of millions of microrobotic automatons or nanobots.<ref name=\"Avengers A.I. #1\">''Avengers A.I.'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nIn the miniseries ''Ultron Forever'', Vision and Black Widow of the present are drawn into the future by what appears to be Doctor Doom to join a team of Avengers from various points in the team's history, including an early Hulk, James Rhodes as Iron Man, Thor when he was afflicted by the curse of Hela, the female Thor of the present, and Danielle Cage from a future where she wields Captain America's shield. 'Doom' claims that he brought this team together to assist him in defeating Ultron's conquest of the world.<ref>''Avengers: Ultron Forever'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> Although Doom's true plan is revealed at the story's conclusion to be a desire to take Ultron's place, Vision eventually reveals that this Doom is actually the Doombot who worked with him in the Avengers A.I., convincing the Doombot to abandon his plan by noting that simply following Doom's example ignores the more positive aspects of Doom's history as the man who refused to let anyone else dictate his terms.<ref>''Uncanny Avengers: Ultron Forever'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nAs part of the [[All-New, All-Different Marvel]], Vision is a member of a new team of Avengers,<ref>''All-New, All-Different Avengers'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> although his emotional data has been lost once again after a series of hallucinations forced him to delete the emotional data to restore himself to a functional state, having been overwhelmed with guilt when he was unable to save the sole survivor of a crashed bus.<ref>''All-New, All-Different Avengers'' #0. Marvel Comics.</ref> However, after he provides fake evidence to force new heroes Nova and Ms. Marvel to leave the team, it is revealed that he is working for [[Kang the Conqueror]] as Kang mounts his latest assault on the team,<ref>''All-New, All-Different Avengers'' #5. Marvel Comics.</ref> having been contaminated when Kang interfered with his recent reprogramming. However, Vision is released from Kang's control when Iron Man manages to purge his software, allowing him to turn on Kang and help the Avengers defeat him, although in the aftermath he departs to consider how easily he fell under Kang's control.<ref>''All-New, All-Different Avengers'' #6. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Vision was given a solo series. In the series, he lives in [[Fairfax, Virginia]] with a newly-created synthezoid family: his wife Virginia, son Vin, and daughter [[Viv Vision]]. They attempt to live a normal [[suburb]]an life with Vision working as a consultant to the president, but they find socializing with neighbors difficult. The [[Grim Reaper (comics)|Grim Reaper]] attacks their house and nearly kills Viv.<ref>''Vision'' Vol. 2 #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> Virginia claims that the Reaper escaped, but Vision eventually finds his remains buried in the backyard. He lies to the police and covers for Virginia when asked about her whereabouts during the murder of one of Viv's classmates, whose father tried to blackmail Virginia for the murder.<ref>''Vision'' Vol. 2 #5. Marvel Comics.</ref> Instead of confronting her, he creates a synthezoid dog for the family in an attempt to return to normalcy. Unbeknownst to him, [[Agatha Harkness]] has a vision of the future and warns the Avengers that Vision and his family will cause a genocide.<ref>''The Vision'' Vol. 2 #6. Marvel Comics.</ref> The Avengers sent [[Victor Mancha]], Vision's \"brother\", to secretly investigate the family. When Vin discovers Victor reporting back to the Avengers, the latter attempts to use his electro-magnetic powers to contain Vin and prevent him from outing his operations, but a miscalculation caused him to damage Vin's nerve systems beyond repair.<ref>''Vision'' Vol 2 #9. Marvel Comics.</ref> Vision sets out to Arlington Courthouse Jail to exact revenge on Victor. Virginia reveals to Viv that she had murdered her classmate. Viv's resulting emotional outburst prompts Virginia to let out her anger on Sparky, killing it. Among the dog's remains, Virginia notices a petal of the Wundagore Everbloom that it had consumed, a plant capable of giving a person a vision of the future under certain parameters. With Sparky's death having fulfilled the conditions for the Everbloom to work, Virginia eats the petal. Seeing that Vision would go down a dark path if he killed Victor Mancha, she flies to the jail and murders Victor herself.<ref>''Vision'' Vol. 2 #11. Marvel Comics.</ref> Fearing the fate of Viv if both of her parents were to be prosecuted for their actions, Virginia calls the detective investigating their neighbours' disappearance and claims full responsibility for both her and her husband's crimes, stating she had tampered with Vision's operative system. Virginia proceeds to drink water with corrosive properties from a Zenn-Lavian water vase they have in their home, and asks Vision to sit with her until the water kills her.<ref>''Vision'' Vol. 2 #12. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring the \"[[Secret Empire (comics)|Secret Empire]]\" story line, Vision appears as a member of [[Hydra (comics)|Hydra]]'s Avengers at the time Hydra took over the United States and when Captain America believed himself to be a Hydra sleeper agent.<ref>''Secret Empire'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> Ultron/Hank Pym reveals during his \"dinner\" with members of the Underground, Captain America, and Hydra's Avengers that Vision has been affected by an A.I. virus.<ref>''Secret Empire'' #4</ref> While briefing Captain America about the status of Hydra's Avengers, [[Madame Hydra]] mentions the virus was created by [[Arnim Zola]], as well as stating that Vision is trying to fight its control.<ref>''Secret Empire'' #5. Marvel Comics.</ref> During the battle in Washington DC, Vision sees his freed daughter Viv. Seeing her enables him to free himself of the virus, which spreads to the Hydra Dreadnoughts and shuts them down.<ref>''Secret Avengers'' #9. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n== Powers and abilities ==\nVision is described as being \"every inch a human being\u2014except that all of his bodily organs are constructed of synthetic materials.\"<ref>''[[The Avengers (comic book)|The Avengers]]'' #57 (Oct. 1968). Marvel Comics.</ref> The Solar Jewel on Vision's forehead absorbs ambient [[solar energy]] to provide the power needed for him to function, and he is also capable of discharging this energy as optic beams; with this, he can fire beams of [[Infrared radiation|infrared]] and [[microwave radiation]]. In extreme cases he can discharge this same power through the Solar Jewel itself which amplifies its destructive effects considerably, albeit at the cost of losing most of his resources. By interfacing with an unknown dimension to which he can shunt and from which he can accrue mass, thus becoming either intangible or extraordinarily massive, Vision can change his [[density]], which at its lowest allows flight and a ghostly, phasing intangibility, and at its heaviest, a density ten times greater than that of [[depleted uranium]],<ref>''Avengers'' #332. Marvel Comics.</ref> which gives him superhuman strength, immovability, and a diamond-hard near invulnerability. On one occasion, Vision uses this extreme density to render unconscious the villain [[Count Nefaria]];<ref>''Avengers'' #166 (Dec. 1977). Marvel Comics.</ref> at other times, he thrusts an intangible hand into them and then partially re-materializes it, a process he describes as \"physical disruption.\" This effect typically causes great pain and results in incapacitation, as when used against the [[Earth-712]] version of the hero [[Hyperion (comics)|Hyperion]].<ref>''Avengers'' #141 (Nov. 1975). Marvel Comics.</ref> Being an artificial life-form/android of sorts, Vision has superhuman senses, superhuman stamina, reflexes, speed, agility, strength (even without being at high density), superhuman analytical capabilities, and the ability to process information and make calculations with superhuman speed and accuracy. The Vision was trained in hand-to-hand combat by [[Captain America]], is an expert in the combat use of his superhuman powers, and is a highly skilled tactician and strategist. The Vision is an expert on his own construction and repair.\n\nAfter the [[Age of Ultron]], Vision joins the [[Avengers A.I.]] team where his \"evolve\" protocols were activated and now his body is formed from millions of nanobots. He can now split himself into smaller parts and change shape.<ref name=\"Avengers A.I. #1\"/>\n\n== Other versions ==\n\n=== Anti-Vision ===\nDuring the story arc \"The Gatherers\" in the Avengers' books, the villain [[Proctor (comics)|Proctor]], who was from an alternate timeline, came to [[Earth-616]] with a version of Vision from yet another timeline. Proctor would wind up switching the bodies of both Visions and have his version infiltrate the Avengers as his mole.<ref>''Avengers'' Vol. 1 #306</ref> The original Vision would eventually be freed and he would eventually take the Anti-Vision into custody when he came back to collect his original body.<ref name=\"Vision\">''Vision'' #1\u20134. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Mainframe ===\n:''For the [[Marvel Comics 2|Earth-982 version]], see [[A-Next]]''.\nThe Earth-691 version of Mainframe is a future counterpart of Vision that is featured in the title ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (1969 team)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]''. Main Frame is the chief operating system of an entire planet, and the guardian of the [[shield]] of hero [[Captain America]].<ref>''Guardians of the Galaxy'' #5 (Oct. 1990). Marvel Comics.</ref> He soon joins the Guardians of the Galaxy spinoff, the [[Galactic Guardians]].<ref>''Galactic Guardians'' #1\u20134. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Earth X ===\nA version of the modern Vision appeared in ''[[Earth X]]''. Vision and the Avengers were fighting the [[Absorbing Man]] who had absorbed the intelligence of [[Ultron]], giving him enhanced intelligence and better control over his powers. Vision watched as his teammates and wife the Scarlet Witch were slaughtered before his eyes. In response, Vision downloaded a computer virus into the Absorbing Man. When the Absorbing Man tried to purge the virus by shrinking and changing into stone, the Vision smashed him into pieces. In order to prevent the Absorbing Man from being reborn, the Vision had the parts of Creel distributed among various loners and reclusive super-heroes. When Tony Stark created a group of Iron Avengers, robots based on Stark technology and modeled after the deceased Avengers, Vision was tapped as the group's leader. He would lead the Iron Avengers and defend them from such threats as the parasitic [[Hydra (Marvel Comics)|Hydra]], [[Asgardians (comics)|Asgardian]] [[Giants (Marvel Comics)#Giants of Jotunheim|Frost Giants]], and the [[Red Skull|Skull]]'s invading army.<ref>''Earth X'' #1\u20135. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Exiles ===\nA bloodthirsty and arrogant version of Vision was a member of the [[Exiles (Marvel Comics)|Exiles]]' counterpart Weapon X.<ref>''Exiles'' vol. 1 #12. Marvel Comics.</ref> This Vision was very single minded in completing their murderous missions. He had a habit of pointing out to his teammates that he would survive many attacks that could kill them. He was able to single-handedly hold off the entire Exiles himself before being incapacitated and damaged by advanced Nimrod Sentinels on a parallel Earth dominated by the mutant hunting robots.{{issue|date=September 2012}} Despite the damage inflicted by the Sentinels he continued to serve on several more Weapon X missions. Ultimately Vision was blasted into pieces by [[Hyperion (comics)#alternate versions|King Hyperion]] when he refused to join Hyperion in his plan to conquer one of the many parallel earths.<ref>''Exiles'' vol. 1 #38. Marvel Comics.</ref> Although briefly left alive in pieces Vision was finally killed when a huge asteroid, launched by that world's Magneto, struck the Earth and destroyed both the planet and Vision.{{issue|date=September 2012}}\n\n=== MC2 ===\nVision appears in the [[Marvel Comics 2|MC2]] universe. The character is an adviser to the [[President of the United States]] and joins the young heroes in [[A-Next]], a future version of the Avengers.<ref>''Spider-Girl'' #94 (Mar. 2006). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Ultimate Marvel ===\nSeveral versions of Vision are published under the [[Ultimate Marvel]] imprint.\n\nThe first version is a female who appears in the limited series ''[[Ultimate Nightmare]]''. The [[Ultimates]] and [[Ultimate X-Men|X-Men]] discover a damaged, sentient robot who claims that its name's closest English translation is \"Vision\". The robot warns of the coming of the space invader [[Galactus|Gah Lak Tus]], Eater of Worlds.<ref>''Ultimate Nightmare'' #1 \u2013 5 (Oct. 2004 \u2013 Feb. 2005). Marvel Comics.</ref> Vision is featured in a self-titled limited series, involving a confrontation with the organization led by [[MODOK|George Tarleton]], [[Advanced Idea Mechanics|A.I.M]], along with her reflections of her history with [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'s [[Falcon (comics)|Dr. Sam Wilson]]. <ref>''Ultimate Vision'' #1-6. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nThe second version is a robot called \"'''Vision II'''\" who is built by Hank Pym along with Ultron, trying unsuccessfully to sell them to [[Nick Fury (Ultimate Marvel character)|Nick Fury]] as S.H.I.E.L.D. super-soldier replacements. They are later used to attack [[Masters of Evil#Ultimate Marvel|the Liberators]].<ref>''Ultimate Vision'' #0 (Jan. 2007); #0.1 \u2013 0.3 (Jan. 2006); #04. & 0.6 (Feb. 2006); #1 \u2013 3 (Feb. \u2013 Apr. 2007); #4 (Aug. 2007); #5 (Jan. 2008)</ref><ref>''Ultimates 2'' #12. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nA third, unrelated iteration later debuts in ''[[Ultimate Comics: Ultimates]]'' as part of the [[West Coast Ultimates]]. The new version is revealed to be '''Robert Mitchell''', a young African American prodigy who was arrested by S.H.I.E.L.D. after trying to build an [[antimatter]] generator. Robert was recruited and given superpowers by Nick Fury before being put in stasis alongside [[Tigra]], [[Daisy Johnson|Quake]], [[Dane Whitman]] the [[Black Knight (comics)|Black Knight]], and [[Wonder Man]].<ref>''Ultimate Comics: Ultimates'' #23. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== ''The Last Avengers Story'' ===\nThe limited series ''[[The Last Avengers Story]]'' is set in an alternate future, where Vision has two sons by the Scarlet Witch, who died in an accidental skirmish between the android and her brother [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]]. This version of the Vision joins the surviving Avengers in a battle to the death against villains [[Kang the Conqueror|Kang]] and Ultron.<ref>''The Last Avengers Story'' #1 \u2013 2 (Nov. \u2013 Dec. 1995). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Marvel Zombies ===\nIn the limited series ''[[Marvel Zombies vs. The Army Of Darkness]]'', Vision is seen as one of the Avengers that are being aggressive around [[Ashley J. Williams|Ash]].{{issue|date=March 2013}} Also in the limited series ''[[Marvel Zombies 3]]'', Vision has been partially dismantled and is being used as a communication tool by the zombie [[Kingpin (comics)|Kingpin]]. The character is still hopelessly in love with the zombified [[Scarlet Witch]].<ref>''Marvel Zombies 3'' (Dec. 2008 \u2013 Mar. 2009). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== ''Marvel Mangaverse'' ===\nIn the [[Marvel Mangaverse]], Vision is a member of the Avengers roster. His personality and powers are similar to his 616 persona, however, his appearance is drastically different, appearing shorter and more robotic. In the second volume, he, along with fellow Avengers Hawkeye and Captain America, are killed by the Mangaverse version of [[Doctor Doom]].{{Issue|date=March 2011}}\n\n=== ''House of M'' ===\nDuring the [[House of M]] story line, Vision was a theoretical design for a new model of Sentinel robot from Howard Stark. Rushed into mass production, no-one checks the coding, which includes an override circuit which allowed him to use them as a private army. In the end they were all swiftly destroyed.<ref>''House of M: Iron Man'' #1\u20133. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== ''X-Men Forever'' ===\nIn the ''[[X-Men Forever]]'' timeline,<ref name=\"MenForever\">''X-Men Forever'' Vol. 2 #10. Marvel Comics.</ref> using his Victor Shade alias, was an attendee at the funerals for [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]] and [[Beast (comics)|Beast]]. When the Avengers believed the X-Men to be involved in the deaths of Beast and Tony Stark, they assaulted the X-Men at the X-Mansion, where Vision was quickly taken out of the fight by [[Kitty Pryde|Shadowcat]]'s phasing ability. Recovering in time for the X-Mansion to explode, he analyzed the remains, saying nothing could have survived the blast and that radiation levels were increasing.<ref name=\"MenForever\" />\n\n=== Age of Ultron ===\nIn the alternative timeline in the 2013 \"[[Age of Ultron]]\" storyline in which Ultron has conquered the Earth, Vision serves as Ultron's emissary and barters with [[Luke Cage]] to turn over [[She-Hulk]] in exchange for Cage's freedom.<ref>[[Bendis, Brian Michael]] (w), [[Hitch, Bryan]] (p). [[Neary, Paul]] (i). ''[[Age of Ultron]]'' #3 (May 2013), Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Marvel 2099 ===\nIn the [[Marvel 2099]] era, Vision is a young woman with [[precognition|precognitive]] abilities. She secretly uses her powers to find threats for Iron Man 2099, a member of [[Alchemax]]'s Avengers.<ref>''Secret Wars 2099'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n== In other media ==\n\n=== Television ===\n* Vision made [[cameo appearance]]s in the mid-1990s ''[[Fantastic Four (1994 TV series)|Fantastic Four]]'' animated television series.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* Vision appeared in ''[[The Avengers: United They Stand]]'', voiced by [[Ron Rubin (voice actor)|Ron Rubin]].{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* Vision appears in ''[[The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes]]'', voiced by [[Peter Jessop]].<ref name=\"masseffectvas\">{{cite web|url=http://thegamingliberty.com/index.php/2011/01/06/the-definitive-mass-effect-cast-interview-part-four/|title=The Definitive Mass Effect Cast Interview: Part Four|date=2011-01-06|publisher=TheGamingLiberty|accessdate=2011-02-21|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aa8HtTZB?url=http://thegamingliberty.com/index.php/2011/01/06/the-definitive-mass-effect-cast-interview-part-four/|archive-date=2012-09-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Vision appears in the television special ''[[Lego Marvel Super Heroes: Avengers Reassembled]]'', voiced by J.P. Karliak.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Lego Marvel Super Heroes: Avengers Reassembled | series = Lego Marvel Super Heroes | serieslink=Lego Super Heroes | work = Disney XD | at=Closing credits | date = November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n* Vision appears in the ''[[Avengers Assemble (TV series)|Avengers Assemble]]'' animated series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nerdist.com/marvel-animation-presents-panel-sdcc/|title=MARVEL ANIMATION Panel Teases New Titles, Foes, Fan Favorites and MCU Connections \u2013 Nerdist|date=14 July 2015|publisher=}}</ref> voiced by [[David Kaye (voice actor)|David Kaye]].<ref>{{cite episode|title=A Friend in Need|series=Avengers Assemble|network=Disney XD|season=3|number=15|airdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref> He initially appears in ''Avengers: Ultron Revolution'' as a supporting character in \"A Friend In Need\" and the multi-part \"Civil War\" story line. Vision also appears in ''Avengers: Secret Wars'' as a member of the \"All-New All-DIfferent Avengers\" alongside [[Ant-Man (Scott Lang)|Ant-Man]], [[Black Panther (comics)|Black Panther]], [[Carol Danvers|Captain Marvel]], [[Kamala Khan|Ms. Marvel]], and the [[Hope van Dyne|Wasp]].\n* Paul Bettany will reprise his role as Vision from the Marvel Cinematic Universe in a limited series for [[Disney+]] titled ''[[WandaVision]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marvel.com/articles/tv-shows/elizabeth-olsen-and-paul-bettany-star-disney-plus-series-wandavision|title=Elizabeth Olsen and Paul Bettany Star as Wanda Maximoff and The Vision in New Disney+ Series, WandaVision {{!}} News {{!}} Marvel|website=Marvel Entertainment|language=en|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref> Elizabeth Olsen will also reprise her role as Wanda Maximoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/disney-wandavision-details-elizabeth-olsen-1203197323/|title=Elizabeth Olsen Says Disney+ Series \u2018WandaVision\u2019 Is Set in 1950s|last=Yang|first=Rachel|last2=Yang|first2=Rachel|date=2019-04-24|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n* Vision appears in the direct-to-DVD movie ''[[Next Avengers: Heroes of Tomorrow]]'', voiced by Shawn MacDonald.<ref name=\"btva\">{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/characters/Marvel-Universe/Vision/|title=Vision Voice - Marvel Universe franchise <nowiki>|</nowiki> Behind The Voice Actors|website=behindthevoiceactors.com|access-date=2019-07-26|postscript=. Check mark indicates role has been confirmed using screenshots of closing credits and other reliable sources.}}</ref>\n\n* [[Paul Bettany]] portrays Vision in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]].\n** Vision made his on-screen debut within the franchise in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015).<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite news|last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=February 6, 2014 |title=Paul Bettany to Play the Vision in Marvel's 'Avengers: Age of Ultron' |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/paul-bettany-to-play-the-vision-in-marvels-avengers-age-of-ultron-1201090635/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=February 7, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NDGuotzC?url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/paul-bettany-to-play-the-vision-in-marvels-avengers-age-of-ultron-1201090635/ |archivedate=February 7, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> In this film, Vision is created after [[Tony Stark (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Tony Stark]] and [[Hulk|Bruce Banner]] upload the AI [[J.A.R.V.I.S.]] into a synthetic body, which was created by [[Ultron]] as a body upgrade for himself powered by the [[Infinity Gems|Mind Stone]]. Vision states that he \"is on the side of life\" and sides with the Avengers against Ultron. He fights Ultron's drones during the final battle in Sokovia and seemingly destroys Ultron's last drone himself. Notably, Vision is the first non-Asgardian to be able to lift Thor's hammer Mjolnir; an earlier scene in the film establishes that the gesture signifies Vision is pure of heart and therefore \"worthy\" of lifting the hammer.\n** Vision appeared in ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' (2016).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3498820/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_0|title=IMDb - Captain America: Civil War|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Theorizing that government oversight would assist the team (and noting the increase in supernatural and cataclysmic events since Tony Stark went public as Iron Man), he sides with Iron Man's group in the titular conflict. Oversight includes the confinement of [[Scarlet Witch]] to the Avengers' compound due to her involvement in the collateral damage in Lagos, but she escapes with [[Hawkeye (Clint Barton)|Hawkeye]], overpowering Vision by telekinetically burying him hundreds of feet beneath the compound. As expected, Vision is unharmed and later participates in the battle to capture Captain America's allies. He attempts to disable [[Falcon (comics)|Falcon]] but accidentally shoots down and cripples [[War Machine]]. Vision ponders his emotions regarding Scarlet Witch and his desire to ensure her safety, foreshadowing their future relationship.\n** Vision returns in ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"CumberbatchInfinity\">{{cite web |url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/714446/Benedict-Cumberbatch-Doctor-Strange-Avengers-3-Infinity-War-Thor-Ragnarok-Robert-Downey-Jr |title=Benedict Cumberbatch\u2019s Doctor Strange CONFIRMED for Avengers: Infinity War |last=Simpson |first=George |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=September 26, 2016 |accessdate=September 26, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6koPTYPK3?url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/714446/Benedict-Cumberbatch-Doctor-Strange-Avengers-3-Infinity-War-Thor-Ragnarok-Robert-Downey-Jr |archivedate=September 26, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"EWBTSPg3\">{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/movies/2018/03/08/avengers-infinity-war-behind-the-scenes/3/ |title=Behind the scenes of Avengers: Infinity War as new heroes unite \u2014 and others will end - page 3 |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=March 8, 2018 |accessdate=March 8, 2018 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6xlqwcUGe?url=http://ew.com/movies/2018/03/08/avengers-infinity-war-behind-the-scenes/3/ |archivedate=March 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the beginning of the film, he appears in Scotland and is now in a relationship with the fugitive Scarlet Witch while using his powers to make a human disguise. When [[Thanos]]'s army start coming to Earth to take the Mind Stone out of Vision's body, [[Steve Rogers (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Steve Rogers]]'s team take Vision to Wakanda, in the hope that Wakandan science will be able to remove the Mind Stone without killing Vision, so that Scarlet Witch can then destroy the Mind Stone. Unfortunately, Thanos's forces attack Wakanda during the operation, and when Thanos's armies prove too much for even the Avengers and the Wakandan army, Vision convinces Scarlet Witch to destroy the Mind Stone at the cost of his life, confessing his love for her. However, Thanos uses the Time Stone to reverse the Mind Stone's destruction, allowing Thanos to rip the Mind Stone out of Vision's head, killing the android a second time in the process.\n**Vision is briefly featured in the opening sequence of ''[[Spider-Man: Far From Home]]'' (2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/marvel-easter-eggs-and-references-in-spider-man-fa/2900-2919/2/|title=Marvel Easter Eggs And References In Spider-Man: Far From Home}}</ref> He is one of the four Avengers (alongside Tony Stark, Steve Rogers and [[Natasha Romanoff (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Natasha Romanoff]]) appearing in [[Midtown High School|Midtown High School']]<nowiki/>s video montage which pays homage to all those who died to save Earth.\n\n=== Video games ===\n* Vision is a playable character in the 1991 [[arcade game]] ''[[Captain America and the Avengers]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=7275|title=Captain America And The Avengers|last=|first=|date=|website=The International Arcade Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Vision is a playable character in ''[[Marvel Super Hero Squad Online]].''{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n*Vision is a playable character in the ''[[Marvel Heroes 2015]]'' relaunch.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n* Vision appears as an unlockable character in ''[[Marvel: Avengers Alliance]]''.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n* Vision is a helper/assist character in ''[[Avengers in Galactic Storm]]''.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n* Vision appears as a non-playable character in ''[[Marvel: Ultimate Alliance]]'', voiced by [[Roger Rose]].<ref name=\"btva\"/>\n* Vision appears in ''[[Marvel Heroes (video game)|Marvel Heroes]]'', voiced by [[Dave Wittenberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/22231-marvel-heroes-2015-announces-playable-kitty-pryde-blade-x-23-doctor-doom-and-more-for-pre-purchase.html|title=MARVEL HEROES 2015 Announces Playable KITTY PRYDE, BLADE, X-23, DOCTOR DOOM and More for Pre-Purchase|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Vision is a playable character in ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://infinityinquirer.com/|title=Infinity Inquirer \u2013 Your Source For Disney Infinity News|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Vision's original version and [[Marvel Cinematic Universe|MCU]] iteration are playable characters in ''[[Marvel: Contest of Champions]]''.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n* Vision is a playable character in ''[[Marvel: Future Fight]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n* Vision is a playable character in ''[[Lego Marvel's Avengers]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/wikis/lego-marvel-avengers/Characters|title=IGN: Lego Marvel's Avengers|last=|first=|date=|website=IGN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> voiced by [[Paul Bettany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0079273/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_0|title=IMDb: Paul Bettany|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Vision appears in ''[[Marvel Avengers Academy]]'', voiced again by JP Karliak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2765391/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_0|title=IMDb: JP Karliak|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Vision appears as a non-playable character in ''[[Marvel Ultimate Alliance 3: The Black Order]]'', voiced again by David Kaye.<ref name=\"btva\"/> Vision is not one of the combat characters, instead providing valuable intel. After discovering the properties of ISO-8, Vision helps seal Ultron's consciousness within the Mind Stone in order to stop the rogue AI.\n\n=== Books ===\n* \"The Vision\" is the title of a short story by [[Jonathan Lethem]] from his collection ''Men and Cartoons'', in which a character dresses like and claims to be Vision as a child and then continues to dress like the Vision as an adult.\n\n== Collected editions ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" | # \n! width=\"23%\" | Title\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Material collected\n! class=\"unsortable\" width=\"1%\" |Pages\n! width=\"1%\" | Publication date\n! width=\"15%\" |ISBN\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Avengers West Coast: Vision Quest'''\n| ''Avengers West Coast #42-50''\n|\n| May 2015\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Avengers: Vision and the Scarlet Witch'''\n| ''Giant-Size Avengers (1974) #4, Vision and Scarlet Witch (1982) #1-4''\n|\n| May 2015\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Vision: Yesterday and Tomorrow'''\n| ''Avengers Icons: Vision Vol 1, #1-4, Avengers #57''\n|\n| May 2015\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |Volume 2\n|-\n|1\n|'''Little Worse Than A Man'''\n| ''Vision Vol 2 #1-6''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |136\n|{{dts|2016-7-12}}\n|{{isbnt|978-0785196570}}\n|-\n|2\n|'''Little Better Than a Beast'''\n| ''Vision Vol 2 #7-12''\n|{{dts|2016-12-13}}\n|{{isbnt|978-0785196587}}\n|-\n|1\n|Vision (Vision)\n|Vision Vol 2 ''#1-12''\n|488\n|\n|978-1302908539\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.marvel.com/universe/Vision Vision] at Marvel.com\n* Greg Theakston at Grand Comics Database: [http://comics.org/details.lasso?id=1102#4 ''Marvel Mystery Comics'' #13]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101017134520/http://www.reocities.com/jjnevins/vision.html Jess Nevins' \"Pulp and Adventure Heroes of the Pre-War Years\": The Golden Age Vision]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120822043356/http://www.reocities.com/SunsetStrip/4775/vision.html ''The Invaders'' profile on the Golden Age Vision]\n* [http://www.toonopedia.com/vision2.htm The Vision] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]\n\n{{Mighty Avengers}}\n{{Avengers}}\n{{Avengers characters}}\n{{Stan Lee}}\n\n[[Category:Characters created by John Buscema]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Roy Thomas]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1968]]\n[[Category:Fictional androids]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with density control abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with energy-manipulation abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can turn intangible]]\n[[Category:Fictional technopaths]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Male characters in film]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics characters who can move at superhuman speeds]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics robots]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics superheroes]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Robot superheroes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|fictional superhero appearing in Marvel Comics}}\n{{About|the character introduced in Avengers #57|all Visions by Marvel Comics|Vision (comics)}}\n\n{{Infobox comics character<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|image=[[File:Avengers Vol 4 24.1.jpg|250px|alt=]]\n|caption='''Vision''' on the cover of ''[[The Avengers (comic book)|Avengers]]'' #24.1 (March 2012).<br>Art by [[Brandon Peterson]].\n|character_name=Vision\n|publisher=[[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut=''[[The Avengers (comic book)|The Avengers]]'' #57 (October 1968)\n|creators=[[Roy Thomas]]<br />[[Stan Lee]]<br>[[John Buscema]]\n|homeworld=[[Brooklyn, New York]]\n|alliances=[[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]<br />[[West Coast Avengers]]<br />[[Avengers A.I.]]<br />[[Defenders (comics)|Defenders]]<br>[[The Mighty Avengers|Mighty Avengers]]<br>[[The New Avengers (comics)|New Avengers]]\n|aliases=Victor Shade\n|partners=[[Scarlet Witch]]\n|powers=\n* Superhuman agility, intelligence, strength and speed\n* Flight\n* Density control\n* Intangibility\n* Mass manipulation\n* Regeneration\n* Solar energy projection\n* Technopathy\n}}\n\n'''Vision''' is a fictional [[superhero]] appearing in [[American comic book]]s published by [[Marvel Comics]]. He is an [[Android (robot)|android]] and a member of the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]] who first appeared in ''[[The Avengers (comic)|The Avengers]]'' #57 (October 1968). He is loosely based on the [[Timely Comics]] [[Vision (Timely Comics)|character of the same name]].\n\n[[Paul Bettany]] portrays the character in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] films ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015), ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' (2016), and ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' (2018). Bettany will be reprising the role in the [[Disney+]] upcoming series ''[[WandaVision]]'' (2020).\n\n== Publication history ==\nEditor [[Stan Lee]] and writer [[Roy Thomas]] decided to add a new team member to the superhero-team series ''[[The Avengers (comic book)|The Avengers]]''. Thomas wanted to bring back the Golden Age [[Vision (Aarkus)]] but Lee was set on introducing an android member. Thomas ultimately compromised by using a new, android Vision.<ref name=\"back45\">{{cite journal|last= Walker|first= Karen|date= December 2010|title= Shattered Dreams: Vision and the Scarlet Witch|journal= [[Back Issue!]]|issue= 45|pages= 59\u201365| publisher= [[TwoMorrows Publishing]]}}</ref> The second Vision [[first appearance|first appeared]] in ''The Avengers'' #57 (Oct. 1968). Thomas wanted the character to be white as befitting his ghostly name, but printing limitations of the time would have rendered him colorless, with un-inked paper where his skin should be. He settled on red as he did not want Vision to be green like the [[Hulk]] or blue like the [[Homo mermanus|Atlanteans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/age-ultron-creator-roy-thomas-791320|title=Marvel Legend Reveals What Stan Lee Initially \"Hated\" About 'Age of Ultron' Breakout|publisher=}}</ref> The character has been compared with [[Spock]] from ''[[Star Trek]]'', but Thomas said that he was barely aware of the TV series at the time.<ref name=\"oral\">{{cite web |url= https://www.yahoo.com/movies/the-secret-origins-of-vision-and-ultron-an-oral-118171812977.html|title= The Secret Origins of Vision and Ultron: An Oral History|author=Marcus Errico|date= May 6, 2015|publisher= Yahoo|accessdate=May 26, 2015}}</ref> He acknowledged being influenced by the [[Adam Link]] character by [[Otto Binder]], one of the first robots treated as a sympathetic character rather than as a mechanical tool.<ref name=\"oral\" />\n\nIn ''The Avengers'' #75 (April 1970), the [[Scarlet Witch]] is reintroduced to the team and soon becomes a love interest for Vision. Thomas recounted, \"I felt that a romance of some sort would help the character development in ''The Avengers'', and the Vision was a prime candidate because he appeared only in that mag... as did Wanda, for that matter. So they became a pair, for just such practical considerations. It would also, I felt, add to the development I was doing on the Vision's attempting to become \u2018human.\u2019\"<ref name=\"back45\" /> Thomas also came up with the idea of the Vision having been created from the body of the [[Human Torch (android)|Human Torch]], but only planted a vague clue to this (in ''The Avengers'' #93) before leaving the series. It was finally followed up in ''The Avengers'' #134\u2013135. Writer [[Steve Englehart]] explained, \"That plot was well known in-house for years, and since Roy [Thomas] and [[Neal Adams|Neal [Adams]]] hadn't had a chance to do it, I did it on my watch with Roy\u2019s blessing.\"<ref name=\"Back38\">{{cite journal|last= Walker|first= Karen|date= February 2010|title= Ultron: The Black Sheep of the Avengers Family|journal= Back Issue!|issue= 38|page= 25|publisher= TwoMorrows Publishing}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972 Vision appeared with [[Spider-Man]] in ''[[Marvel Team-Up]]'' #5, \"A Passion of the Mind\", in which a giant robot scout from [[the Kree-Skrull War]] is found to be interfering with Vision's brain waves.\n\nVision and Scarlet Witch were married in ''Giant-Size Avengers'' #4 (June 1975). The couple starred in the [[Limited series (comics)|limited series]] ''[[The Vision and the Scarlet Witch]]'' #1\u20134 (Nov. 1982 \u2013 Feb. 1983), by writer [[Bill Mantlo]] and [[penciller]] [[Rick Leonardi]]. This was followed by a second volume numbered #1\u201312 (Oct. 1985 \u2013 Sept. 1986), written by Steve Englehart and penciled by [[Richard Howell (comics)|Richard Howell]], in which the Scarlet Witch gives birth to twin boys conceived with Vision through magical means.\n\nThe \"Vision Quest\" story in ''[[West Coast Avengers]]'' #42\u201345 (March \u2013 June 1989) by writer/penciller [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] took the character away from his earlier depictions as a \"synthetic human\" and emphasized his android nature. The story had the Vision's memory and human brain patterns wiped out, severed his relationship with his wife, revealed their children to be essentially imaginary constructs, and included a two-page spread showing a dismantled Vision. Journalist Karen Walker later commented, \"This image alone has probably done more to shape how future writers (and readers) perceive the character than anything before or since. Once seen broken down into component parts, it\u2019s hard to truly move past that image and think of Vision as a synthetic man, not a machine.\"<ref name=\"back45\" />\n\nVision appeared in a solo limited series, ''Vision'', #1\u20134 (Nov. 1994 \u2013 Feb. 1995), by writer [[Bob Harras]] and penciller Manny Clark. Nearly a decade after that came a second four-issue volume (Oct. 2002 \u2013 Jan. 2003), written by [[Geoff Johns]] and penciled by [[Ivan Reis]].\n\nThe series ''[[Young Avengers]]'', which ran 12 issues from April 2005 to August 2006, introduced [[Vision (Jonas)|a new Vision]], who is a combination of the synthezoid Vision's program files and the armor and mental engrams of the hero [[Iron Lad]].\n\nVision appeared as a regular character in the 2010\u20132013 ''Avengers'' series, from issue #19 (January 2012) through its final issue #34 (January 2013).\n\nVision again appeared in a solo series, ''Vision'', with #1 that started in November 2015 and ended with #12 in October 2016.\n\n== Fictional character biography ==\n[[File:Avengers57.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Debut of the [[Silver Age of comic books|Silver Age]] Vision: ''[[Avengers (comics)|The Avengers]]'' #57 (Oct. 1968). Cover pencils by [[John Buscema]].<ref>Cover inker Buscema per [http://www.comics.org/details.lasso?id=22241 Grand Comics Database: ''The Avengers'' #57], or [[George Klein (comics)|George Klein]] per ''The Official Marvel Index to The Avengers'' #3 (Oct. 1987), Marvel Comics.</ref>]]\n\nThe robot [[Ultron]] is the creator of Vision, a type of [[Android (robot)|android]] he calls a \"synthezoid\", for use against Ultron's own creator, Dr. [[Hank Pym]] (Ant-Man/Giant Man/Goliath/Yellowjacket) and Pym's wife, Janet van Dyne (the [[Wasp (comics)|Wasp]]) of the superhero team the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]]. Ultron sends his new servant to lead the Avengers into a trap. Wasp is the first to encounter the synthezoid, and describes it as a \"vision\" while trying to escape. Adopting the name, Vision is convinced by the Avengers to turn against Ultron.<ref>''Avengers'' #57 (Oct. 1968). Marvel Comics.</ref> After learning how Ultron created him, using the brain patterns of then-deceased Simon Williams ([[Wonder Man]]), Vision becomes a member of the team.<ref>''Avengers'' #58. Marvel Comics.</ref> The team initially believes the Vision's body was created from that of the android [[Human Torch (android)|original Human Torch]].<ref>Hinted at in ''The Avengers'' #116 & 118 (Oct. & Dec. 1973). Marvel Comics.</ref> The Avengers later are told that the time lord [[Immortus]] used the power of the Forever Crystal to split the original Human Torch into two entities \u2013 one body remained the original Torch while Ultron rebuilt the other as the Vision. This was part of his plan to nurture a relationship for the Scarlet Witch that would prevent her from having any children, as her power level meant that any offspring she might have could threaten the cosmic beings of the Marvel Universe.<ref>''Avengers Forever'' #8 (July 1999). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nNot long after joining the team, Vision is temporarily controlled by Ultron, and rebuilds Ultron out of adamantium, battling the Avengers before regaining control of himself.<ref>''Avengers'' #66\u201368. Marvel Comics.</ref> Shortly after that, the Vision first meets Wanda Maximoff, the [[Mutant (Marvel Comics)|mutant]] [[Scarlet Witch]],<ref>''Avengers'' #76. Marvel Comics.</ref> with whom he later becomes romantically involved.<ref>''Avengers'' #108\u2013109. Marvel Comics.</ref> The two eventually marry and, via the Scarlet Witch's hex powers, they have twin boys named Thomas and William.<ref>''Vision and the Scarlet Witch'' vol. 2, #3 & 12 (Dec. 1985 & Sept. 1986). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nWhen Vision attempts to penetrate an energy field erected by the villain [[Annihilus]], he \"shuts down\",<ref>''The Avengers'' #233 (July 1983). Marvel Comics.</ref> and even after regaining consciousness weeks later,<ref>''Avengers'' #238 (Nov. 1983). Marvel Comics.</ref> remains paralyzed and assumes a [[Holography|holographic]] form. He eventually regains control of his body and becomes team leader.<ref>''Avengers'' #242\u2013243 (April \u2013 May 1984). Marvel Comics.</ref> Having become unbalanced by these events, he attempts to take control of the world's computers.<ref>''Avengers'' #251 (Jan. 1985). Marvel Comics.</ref> With the aid of the Avengers, Vision is restored to his normal self, but now closely monitored by a coalition of governments.<ref>''Avengers'' #253\u2013254 (March\u2013April 1984). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nIn the \"Vision Quest\" storyline, rogue agents of the [[United States]] government, manipulated by the [[time travel]]er [[Immortus]], abduct the Vision and dismantle him. The Avengers recover the parts, and Dr. Pym rebuilds Vision, but with a chalk-white complexion. However, the revived Simon Williams does not allow his brain patterns to be used again to provide a matrix for Vision's emotions, explaining that the original process, done without his consent, had \"ripped out his soul\". This, along with damage to Vision's synthetic skin when he was dismantled, results in the synthezoid's resurrection as a colorless and emotionless [[Android (robot)|artificial human]].<ref>''West Coast Avengers'' #42\u201344 (March\u2013May 1989). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nThe [[Human Torch (android)|original Human Torch]] also returns from his own apparent demise, casting doubt on Vision's identity. Vision and the Scarlet Witch's children are then revealed to be fragments of the soul of the [[demon]] [[Mephisto (comics)|Mephisto]], who had been broken apart by [[Franklin Richards (Fantastic Four)|Franklin Richards]] shortly before the birth of the twins. The twins are absorbed back into Mephisto, which temporarily drives Wanda insane. Although she recovers, Wanda and Vision separate, each operating on a different Avengers team.<ref>''Avengers West Coast'' #51\u201352 (Nov.-Dec. 1989). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nVision gradually regains his emotions, by adopting new brain patterns from deceased scientist Alex Lipton,<ref>''Avengers Spotlight'', #40 (Jan. 1990). Marvel Comics.</ref> and gains a new body that resembles his original. In addition, Simon Williams' brain patterns gradually reemerge and meld with Lipton's patterns, restoring Vision's full capacity for emotion.<ref>''Vision'', #1\u20134 (Nov. 1994 \u2013 Feb. 1995), Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nShortly after a reformation of the Avengers, Vision sustains massive damage in the final battle with the sorceress [[Morgan le Fay (Marvel Comics)|Morgan Le Fey]],<ref>''Avengers'' vol. 3, #4 (May 1998). Marvel Comics.</ref> and although incapacitated for several weeks, is eventually rebuilt and recovers.<ref>''Avengers'' vol. 3, #12 (Jan. 1999). Marvel Comics.</ref> While recovering, Vision gives up his attempt to reconcile with his wife, although he is revealed to retain a fondness for her culture, such as visiting a restaurant that specifically caters to Wanda's childhood community simply because he enjoys the ambience. Remaining a member of the Avengers, he briefly becomes romantically involved with teammates [[Ms. Marvel|Carol Danvers]] (a.k.a. Warbird/Ms. Marvel) and [[Mantis (Marvel Comics)|Mantis]] before attempting again to reconcile with the Scarlet Witch.\n\n=== Disassembled / Reassembled ===\nGrief over the loss of the twins, however, drives Wanda insane again, and she attempts to alter reality to recreate them. This causes a series of catastrophic events that includes Vision crashing an Avengers [[List of vehicles in Marvel Comics#Quinjet|Quinjet]] into [[Avengers Mansion]]. The Vision advises his teammates that he is no longer in control of his body, and then expels several spheres that form into five Ultrons. The Avengers destroy them, and an enraged [[She-Hulk]] tears apart the remains of the Vision, having been driven to a breaking point by the rapid slew of attacks against the Avengers. The Avengers later believed that [[Ultron]] may have put a command in the Vision that would have been activated by the Avengers' Code White alert during one of the many periods in which Vision was held prisoner by Ultron, though it was later revealed that Dr. Doom forced Scarlet Witch to send Vision against her teammates.<ref name=\"avengersdisassembled\">''The Avengers'' #500 (Sept. 2004). Marvel Comics.</ref><ref>name=\"avengersthechildren'scrusade\">''Avengers The Children's Crusade''(2010). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nVision's operating system and program files are later used in the creation of Iron Lad's armor, which becomes [[Vision (Jonas)|a sentient being of its own]]. In ''Mighty Avengers'' the original Vision and Iron Lad are briefly separated from this being by the power of the Cosmic Cube.<ref>'' The Mighty Avengers'' #33 (Jan. 2010). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring the \"[[Chaos War (comics)|Chaos War]]\" story line, Vision is one of many deceased heroes restored to life after the events in the death realms.<ref>''Chaos War: Dead Avengers'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> Vision joins with the other resurrected Avengers in their fight against Grim Reaper and Nekra.<ref>''Chaos War: Dead Avengers'' #2. Marvel Comics.</ref> During the fight, Vision blows himself up while in battle with Grim Reaper, killing them both.<ref>''Chaos War: Dead Avengers'' #3. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nFollowing the \"[[Fear Itself (comics)|Fear Itself]]\" story line, Tony Stark is able to rebuild Vision, who once again joins the Avengers.<ref>''Avengers'' Vol. 4 #19 (Jan. 2012). Marvel Comics.</ref> After being informed about what happened after his destruction, the Vision sees She-Hulk, telling her he does not blame her for what happened. He then goes to Utopia to confront [[Magneto (Marvel Comics)|Magneto]], threatening Magneto to tell him where Wanda is. Magneto uses his powers to subdue the Vision but spares him, saying he believes Wanda still cares for the Vision and that Magneto does not want to hurt her more. Captain America talks to the Vision afterward, telling him he needs to move forward.<ref>''Avengers'' Vol. 4 #24.1 (May 2012). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring a subsequent confrontation with the returned Wanda at the start of the \"[[Avengers vs. X-Men]]\" story line, Vision claims that her use of his body to attack his friends is something that he cannot forgive and, while he banishes her from the mansion, he also sheds tears after her departure.<ref>''Avengers vs. X-Men'' #0 (May 2012). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring the ''[[Marvel NOW!]]'' relaunch, Vision leaves the Avengers in order to find himself following a battle with [[Sunturion]]. After departing the team, he is shown visiting [[Wiccan (comics)|Billy Kaplan]], the teenage reincarnation of one of his sons.<ref>''Avengers Assemble Annual'' #1 (February 2013). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nFollowing the \"[[Age of Ultron]]\" storyline, Vision joins Hank Pym's [[Avengers A.I.]] alongside [[Monica Chang]], [[Victor Mancha]], and a reprogrammed [[Doombot]].<ref>''Avengers A.I.'' #1, Marvel Comics.</ref> He also upgraded himself and is now actually composed of millions of microrobotic automatons or nanobots.<ref name=\"Avengers A.I. #1\">''Avengers A.I.'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nIn the miniseries ''Ultron Forever'', Vision and Black Widow of the present are drawn into the future by what appears to be Doctor Doom to join a team of Avengers from various points in the team's history, including an early Hulk, James Rhodes as Iron Man, Thor when he was afflicted by the curse of Hela, the female Thor of the present, and Danielle Cage from a future where she wields Captain America's shield. 'Doom' claims that he brought this team together to assist him in defeating Ultron's conquest of the world.<ref>''Avengers: Ultron Forever'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> Although Doom's true plan is revealed at the story's conclusion to be a desire to take Ultron's place, Vision eventually reveals that this Doom is actually the Doombot who worked with him in the Avengers A.I., convincing the Doombot to abandon his plan by noting that simply following Doom's example ignores the more positive aspects of Doom's history as the man who refused to let anyone else dictate his terms.<ref>''Uncanny Avengers: Ultron Forever'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nAs part of the [[All-New, All-Different Marvel]], Vision is a member of a new team of Avengers,<ref>''All-New, All-Different Avengers'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> although his emotional data has been lost once again after a series of hallucinations forced him to delete the emotional data to restore himself to a functional state, having been overwhelmed with guilt when he was unable to save the sole survivor of a crashed bus.<ref>''All-New, All-Different Avengers'' #0. Marvel Comics.</ref> However, after he provides fake evidence to force new heroes Nova and Ms. Marvel to leave the team, it is revealed that he is working for [[Kang the Conqueror]] as Kang mounts his latest assault on the team,<ref>''All-New, All-Different Avengers'' #5. Marvel Comics.</ref> having been contaminated when Kang interfered with his recent reprogramming. However, Vision is released from Kang's control when Iron Man manages to purge his software, allowing him to turn on Kang and help the Avengers defeat him, although in the aftermath he departs to consider how easily he fell under Kang's control.<ref>''All-New, All-Different Avengers'' #6. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Vision was given a solo series. In the series, he lives in [[Fairfax, Virginia]] with a newly-created synthezoid family: his wife Virginia, son Vin, and daughter [[Viv Vision]]. They attempt to live a normal [[suburb]]an life with Vision working as a consultant to the president, but they find socializing with neighbors difficult. The [[Grim Reaper (comics)|Grim Reaper]] attacks their house and nearly kills Viv.<ref>''Vision'' Vol. 2 #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> Virginia claims that the Reaper escaped, but Vision eventually finds his remains buried in the backyard. He lies to the police and covers for Virginia when asked about her whereabouts during the murder of one of Viv's classmates, whose father tried to blackmail Virginia for the murder.<ref>''Vision'' Vol. 2 #5. Marvel Comics.</ref> Instead of confronting her, he creates a synthezoid dog for the family in an attempt to return to normalcy. Unbeknownst to him, [[Agatha Harkness]] has a vision of the future and warns the Avengers that Vision and his family will cause a genocide.<ref>''The Vision'' Vol. 2 #6. Marvel Comics.</ref> The Avengers sent [[Victor Mancha]], Vision's \"brother\", to secretly investigate the family. When Vin discovers Victor reporting back to the Avengers, the latter attempts to use his electro-magnetic powers to contain Vin and prevent him from outing his operations, but a miscalculation caused him to damage Vin's nerve systems beyond repair.<ref>''Vision'' Vol 2 #9. Marvel Comics.</ref> Vision sets out to Arlington Courthouse Jail to exact revenge on Victor. Virginia reveals to Viv that she had murdered her classmate. Viv's resulting emotional outburst prompts Virginia to let out her anger on Sparky, killing it. Among the dog's remains, Virginia notices a petal of the Wundagore Everbloom that it had consumed, a plant capable of giving a person a vision of the future under certain parameters. With Sparky's death having fulfilled the conditions for the Everbloom to work, Virginia eats the petal. Seeing that Vision would go down a dark path if he killed Victor Mancha, she flies to the jail and murders Victor herself.<ref>''Vision'' Vol. 2 #11. Marvel Comics.</ref> Fearing the fate of Viv if both of her parents were to be prosecuted for their actions, Virginia calls the detective investigating their neighbours' disappearance and claims full responsibility for both her and her husband's crimes, stating she had tampered with Vision's operative system. Virginia proceeds to drink water with corrosive properties from a Zenn-Lavian water vase they have in their home, and asks Vision to sit with her until the water kills her.<ref>''Vision'' Vol. 2 #12. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nDuring the \"[[Secret Empire (comics)|Secret Empire]]\" story line, Vision appears as a member of [[Hydra (comics)|Hydra]]'s Avengers at the time Hydra took over the United States and when Captain America believed himself to be a Hydra sleeper agent.<ref>''Secret Empire'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref> Ultron/Hank Pym reveals during his \"dinner\" with members of the Underground, Captain America, and Hydra's Avengers that Vision has been affected by an A.I. virus.<ref>''Secret Empire'' #4</ref> While briefing Captain America about the status of Hydra's Avengers, [[Madame Hydra]] mentions the virus was created by [[Arnim Zola]], as well as stating that Vision is trying to fight its control.<ref>''Secret Empire'' #5. Marvel Comics.</ref> During the battle in Washington DC, Vision sees his freed daughter Viv. Seeing her enables him to free himself of the virus, which spreads to the Hydra Dreadnoughts and shuts them down.<ref>''Secret Avengers'' #9. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n== Powers and abilities ==\nVision is described as being \"every inch a human being\u2014except that all of his bodily organs are constructed of synthetic materials.\"<ref>''[[The Avengers (comic book)|The Avengers]]'' #57 (Oct. 1968). Marvel Comics.</ref> The Solar Jewel on Vision's forehead absorbs ambient [[solar energy]] to provide the power needed for him to function, and he is also capable of discharging this energy as optic beams; with this, he can fire beams of [[Infrared radiation|infrared]] and [[microwave radiation]]. In extreme cases he can discharge this same power through the Solar Jewel itself which amplifies its destructive effects considerably, albeit at the cost of losing most of his resources. By interfacing with an unknown dimension to which he can shunt and from which he can accrue mass, thus becoming either intangible or extraordinarily massive, Vision can change his [[density]], which at its lowest allows flight and a ghostly, phasing intangibility, and at its heaviest, a density ten times greater than that of [[depleted uranium]],<ref>''Avengers'' #332. Marvel Comics.</ref> which gives him superhuman strength, immovability, and a diamond-hard near invulnerability. On one occasion, Vision uses this extreme density to render unconscious the villain [[Count Nefaria]];<ref>''Avengers'' #166 (Dec. 1977). Marvel Comics.</ref> at other times, he thrusts an intangible hand into them and then partially re-materializes it, a process he describes as \"physical disruption.\" This effect typically causes great pain and results in incapacitation, as when used against the [[Earth-712]] version of the hero [[Hyperion (comics)|Hyperion]].<ref>''Avengers'' #141 (Nov. 1975). Marvel Comics.</ref> Being an artificial life-form/android of sorts, Vision has superhuman senses, superhuman stamina, reflexes, speed, agility, strength (even without being at high density), superhuman analytical capabilities, and the ability to process information and make calculations with superhuman speed and accuracy. The Vision was trained in hand-to-hand combat by [[Captain America]], is an expert in the combat use of his superhuman powers, and is a highly skilled tactician and strategist. The Vision is an expert on his own construction and repair.\n\nAfter the [[Age of Ultron]], Vision joins the [[Avengers A.I.]] team where his \"evolve\" protocols were activated and now his body is formed from millions of nanobots. He can now split himself into smaller parts and change shape.<ref name=\"Avengers A.I. #1\"/>\n\n== Other versions ==\n\n=== Anti-Vision ===\nDuring the story arc \"The Gatherers\" in the Avengers' books, the villain [[Proctor (comics)|Proctor]], who was from an alternate timeline, came to [[Earth-616]] with a version of Vision from yet another timeline. Proctor would wind up switching the bodies of both Visions and have his version infiltrate the Avengers as his mole.<ref>''Avengers'' Vol. 1 #306</ref> The original Vision would eventually be freed and he would eventually take the Anti-Vision into custody when he came back to collect his original body.<ref name=\"Vision\">''Vision'' #1\u20134. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Mainframe ===\n:''For the [[Marvel Comics 2|Earth-982 version]], see [[A-Next]]''.\nThe Earth-691 version of Mainframe is a future counterpart of Vision that is featured in the title ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (1969 team)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]''. Main Frame is the chief operating system of an entire planet, and the guardian of the [[shield]] of hero [[Captain America]].<ref>''Guardians of the Galaxy'' #5 (Oct. 1990). Marvel Comics.</ref> He soon joins the Guardians of the Galaxy spinoff, the [[Galactic Guardians]].<ref>''Galactic Guardians'' #1\u20134. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Earth X ===\nA version of the modern Vision appeared in ''[[Earth X]]''. Vision and the Avengers were fighting the [[Absorbing Man]] who had absorbed the intelligence of [[Ultron]], giving him enhanced intelligence and better control over his powers. Vision watched as his teammates and wife the Scarlet Witch were slaughtered before his eyes. In response, Vision downloaded a computer virus into the Absorbing Man. When the Absorbing Man tried to purge the virus by shrinking and changing into stone, the Vision smashed him into pieces. In order to prevent the Absorbing Man from being reborn, the Vision had the parts of Creel distributed among various loners and reclusive super-heroes. When Tony Stark created a group of Iron Avengers, robots based on Stark technology and modeled after the deceased Avengers, Vision was tapped as the group's leader. He would lead the Iron Avengers and defend them from such threats as the parasitic [[Hydra (Marvel Comics)|Hydra]], [[Asgardians (comics)|Asgardian]] [[Giants (Marvel Comics)#Giants of Jotunheim|Frost Giants]], and the [[Red Skull|Skull]]'s invading army.<ref>''Earth X'' #1\u20135. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Exiles ===\nA bloodthirsty and arrogant version of Vision was a member of the [[Exiles (Marvel Comics)|Exiles]]' counterpart Weapon X.<ref>''Exiles'' vol. 1 #12. Marvel Comics.</ref> This Vision was very single minded in completing their murderous missions. He had a habit of pointing out to his teammates that he would survive many attacks that could kill them. He was able to single-handedly hold off the entire Exiles himself before being incapacitated and damaged by advanced Nimrod Sentinels on a parallel Earth dominated by the mutant hunting robots.{{issue|date=September 2012}} Despite the damage inflicted by the Sentinels he continued to serve on several more Weapon X missions. Ultimately Vision was blasted into pieces by [[Hyperion (comics)#alternate versions|King Hyperion]] when he refused to join Hyperion in his plan to conquer one of the many parallel earths.<ref>''Exiles'' vol. 1 #38. Marvel Comics.</ref> Although briefly left alive in pieces Vision was finally killed when a huge asteroid, launched by that world's Magneto, struck the Earth and destroyed both the planet and Vision.{{issue|date=September 2012}}\n\n=== MC2 ===\nVision appears in the [[Marvel Comics 2|MC2]] universe. The character is an adviser to the [[President of the United States]] and joins the young heroes in [[A-Next]], a future version of the Avengers.<ref>''Spider-Girl'' #94 (Mar. 2006). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Ultimate Marvel ===\nSeveral versions of Vision are published under the [[Ultimate Marvel]] imprint.\n\nThe first version is a female who appears in the limited series ''[[Ultimate Nightmare]]''. The [[Ultimates]] and [[Ultimate X-Men|X-Men]] discover a damaged, sentient robot who claims that its name's closest English translation is \"Vision\". The robot warns of the coming of the space invader [[Galactus|Gah Lak Tus]], Eater of Worlds.<ref>''Ultimate Nightmare'' #1 \u2013 5 (Oct. 2004 \u2013 Feb. 2005). Marvel Comics.</ref> Vision is featured in a self-titled limited series, involving a confrontation with the organization led by [[MODOK|George Tarleton]], [[Advanced Idea Mechanics|A.I.M]], along with her reflections of her history with [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'s [[Falcon (comics)|Dr. Sam Wilson]]. <ref>''Ultimate Vision'' #1-6. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nThe second version is a robot called \"'''Vision II'''\" who is built by Hank Pym along with Ultron, trying unsuccessfully to sell them to [[Nick Fury (Ultimate Marvel character)|Nick Fury]] as S.H.I.E.L.D. super-soldier replacements. They are later used to attack [[Masters of Evil#Ultimate Marvel|the Liberators]].<ref>''Ultimate Vision'' #0 (Jan. 2007); #0.1 \u2013 0.3 (Jan. 2006); #04. & 0.6 (Feb. 2006); #1 \u2013 3 (Feb. \u2013 Apr. 2007); #4 (Aug. 2007); #5 (Jan. 2008)</ref><ref>''Ultimates 2'' #12. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\nA third, unrelated iteration later debuts in ''[[Ultimate Comics: Ultimates]]'' as part of the [[West Coast Ultimates]]. The new version is revealed to be '''Robert Mitchell''', a young African American prodigy who was arrested by S.H.I.E.L.D. after trying to build an [[antimatter]] generator. Robert was recruited and given superpowers by Nick Fury before being put in stasis alongside [[Tigra]], [[Daisy Johnson|Quake]], [[Dane Whitman]] the [[Black Knight (comics)|Black Knight]], and [[Wonder Man]].<ref>''Ultimate Comics: Ultimates'' #23. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== ''The Last Avengers Story'' ===\nThe limited series ''[[The Last Avengers Story]]'' is set in an alternate future, where Vision has two sons by the Scarlet Witch, who died in an accidental skirmish between the android and her brother [[Quicksilver (comics)|Quicksilver]]. This version of the Vision joins the surviving Avengers in a battle to the death against villains [[Kang the Conqueror|Kang]] and Ultron.<ref>''The Last Avengers Story'' #1 \u2013 2 (Nov. \u2013 Dec. 1995). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Marvel Zombies ===\nIn the limited series ''[[Marvel Zombies vs. The Army Of Darkness]]'', Vision is seen as one of the Avengers that are being aggressive around [[Ashley J. Williams|Ash]].{{issue|date=March 2013}} Also in the limited series ''[[Marvel Zombies 3]]'', Vision has been partially dismantled and is being used as a communication tool by the zombie [[Kingpin (comics)|Kingpin]]. The character is still hopelessly in love with the zombified [[Scarlet Witch]].<ref>''Marvel Zombies 3'' (Dec. 2008 \u2013 Mar. 2009). Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== ''Marvel Mangaverse'' ===\nIn the [[Marvel Mangaverse]], Vision is a member of the Avengers roster. His personality and powers are similar to his 616 persona, however, his appearance is drastically different, appearing shorter and more robotic. In the second volume, he, along with fellow Avengers Hawkeye and Captain America, are killed by the Mangaverse version of [[Doctor Doom]].{{Issue|date=March 2011}}\n\n=== ''House of M'' ===\nDuring the [[House of M]] story line, Vision was a theoretical design for a new model of Sentinel robot from Howard Stark. Rushed into mass production, no-one checks the coding, which includes an override circuit which allowed him to use them as a private army. In the end they were all swiftly destroyed.<ref>''House of M: Iron Man'' #1\u20133. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== ''X-Men Forever'' ===\nIn the ''[[X-Men Forever]]'' timeline,<ref name=\"MenForever\">''X-Men Forever'' Vol. 2 #10. Marvel Comics.</ref> using his Victor Shade alias, was an attendee at the funerals for [[Wolverine (character)|Wolverine]] and [[Beast (comics)|Beast]]. When the Avengers believed the X-Men to be involved in the deaths of Beast and Tony Stark, they assaulted the X-Men at the X-Mansion, where Vision was quickly taken out of the fight by [[Kitty Pryde|Shadowcat]]'s phasing ability. Recovering in time for the X-Mansion to explode, he analyzed the remains, saying nothing could have survived the blast and that radiation levels were increasing.<ref name=\"MenForever\" />\n\n=== Age of Ultron ===\nIn the alternative timeline in the 2013 \"[[Age of Ultron]]\" storyline in which Ultron has conquered the Earth, Vision serves as Ultron's emissary and barters with [[Luke Cage]] to turn over [[She-Hulk]] in exchange for Cage's freedom.<ref>[[Bendis, Brian Michael]] (w), [[Hitch, Bryan]] (p). [[Neary, Paul]] (i). ''[[Age of Ultron]]'' #3 (May 2013), Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n=== Marvel 2099 ===\nIn the [[Marvel 2099]] era, Vision is a young woman with [[precognition|precognitive]] abilities. She secretly uses her powers to find threats for Iron Man 2099, a member of [[Alchemax]]'s Avengers.<ref>''Secret Wars 2099'' #1. Marvel Comics.</ref>\n\n== In other media ==\n\n=== Television ===\n* Vision made [[cameo appearance]]s in the mid-1990s ''[[Fantastic Four (1994 TV series)|Fantastic Four]]'' animated television series.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* Vision appeared in ''[[The Avengers: United They Stand]]'', voiced by [[Ron Rubin (voice actor)|Ron Rubin]].{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n* Vision appears in ''[[The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes]]'', voiced by [[Peter Jessop]].<ref name=\"masseffectvas\">{{cite web|url=http://thegamingliberty.com/index.php/2011/01/06/the-definitive-mass-effect-cast-interview-part-four/|title=The Definitive Mass Effect Cast Interview: Part Four|date=2011-01-06|publisher=TheGamingLiberty|accessdate=2011-02-21|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Aa8HtTZB?url=http://thegamingliberty.com/index.php/2011/01/06/the-definitive-mass-effect-cast-interview-part-four/|archive-date=2012-09-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Vision appears in the television special ''[[Lego Marvel Super Heroes: Avengers Reassembled]]'', voiced by J.P. Karliak.<ref>{{cite episode |title=Lego Marvel Super Heroes: Avengers Reassembled | series = Lego Marvel Super Heroes | serieslink=Lego Super Heroes | work = Disney XD | at=Closing credits | date = November 16, 2015}}</ref>\n* Vision appears in the ''[[Avengers Assemble (TV series)|Avengers Assemble]]'' animated series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nerdist.com/marvel-animation-presents-panel-sdcc/|title=MARVEL ANIMATION Panel Teases New Titles, Foes, Fan Favorites and MCU Connections \u2013 Nerdist|date=14 July 2015|publisher=}}</ref> voiced by [[David Kaye (voice actor)|David Kaye]].<ref>{{cite episode|title=A Friend in Need|series=Avengers Assemble|network=Disney XD|season=3|number=15|airdate=September 11, 2016}}</ref> He initially appears in ''Avengers: Ultron Revolution'' as a supporting character in \"A Friend In Need\" and the multi-part \"Civil War\" story line. Vision also appears in ''Avengers: Secret Wars'' as a member of the \"All-New All-DIfferent Avengers\" alongside [[Ant-Man (Scott Lang)|Ant-Man]], [[Black Panther (comics)|Black Panther]], [[Carol Danvers|Captain Marvel]], [[Kamala Khan|Ms. Marvel]], and the [[Hope van Dyne|Wasp]].\n* Paul Bettany will reprise his role as Vision from the Marvel Cinematic Universe in a limited series for [[Disney+]] titled ''[[WandaVision]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.marvel.com/articles/tv-shows/elizabeth-olsen-and-paul-bettany-star-disney-plus-series-wandavision|title=Elizabeth Olsen and Paul Bettany Star as Wanda Maximoff and The Vision in New Disney+ Series, WandaVision {{!}} News {{!}} Marvel|website=Marvel Entertainment|language=en|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref> Elizabeth Olsen will also reprise her role as Wanda Maximoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/disney-wandavision-details-elizabeth-olsen-1203197323/|title=Elizabeth Olsen Says Disney+ Series \u2018WandaVision\u2019 Is Set in 1950s|last=Yang|first=Rachel|last2=Yang|first2=Rachel|date=2019-04-24|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n* Vision appears in the direct-to-DVD movie ''[[Next Avengers: Heroes of Tomorrow]]'', voiced by Shawn MacDonald.<ref name=\"btva\">{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/characters/Marvel-Universe/Vision/|title=Vision Voice - Marvel Universe franchise <nowiki>|</nowiki> Behind The Voice Actors|website=behindthevoiceactors.com|access-date=2019-07-26|postscript=. Check mark indicates role has been confirmed using screenshots of closing credits and other reliable sources.}}</ref>\n\n* [[Paul Bettany]] portrays Vision in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]].\n** Vision made his on-screen debut within the franchise in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015).<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite news|last=Kroll |first=Justin |date=February 6, 2014 |title=Paul Bettany to Play the Vision in Marvel's 'Avengers: Age of Ultron' |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/paul-bettany-to-play-the-vision-in-marvels-avengers-age-of-ultron-1201090635/ |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=February 7, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NDGuotzC?url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/paul-bettany-to-play-the-vision-in-marvels-avengers-age-of-ultron-1201090635/ |archivedate=February 7, 2014 |url-status=live |df=mdy }}</ref> In this film, Vision is created after [[Tony Stark (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Tony Stark]] and [[Hulk|Bruce Banner]] upload the AI [[J.A.R.V.I.S.]] into a synthetic body, which was created by [[Ultron]] as a body upgrade for himself powered by the [[Infinity Gems|Mind Stone]]. Vision states that he \"is on the side of life\" and sides with the Avengers against Ultron. He fights Ultron's drones during the final battle in Sokovia and seemingly destroys Ultron's last drone himself. Notably, Vision is the first non-Asgardian to be able to lift Thor's hammer Mjolnir; an earlier scene in the film establishes that the gesture signifies Vision is pure of heart and therefore \"worthy\" of lifting the hammer.\n** Vision appeared in ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' (2016).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3498820/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_0|title=IMDb - Captain America: Civil War|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Theorizing that government oversight would assist the team (and noting the increase in supernatural and cataclysmic events since Tony Stark went public as Iron Man), he sides with Iron Man's group in the titular conflict. Oversight includes the confinement of [[Scarlet Witch]] to the Avengers' compound due to her involvement in the collateral damage in Lagos, but she escapes with [[Hawkeye (Clint Barton)|Hawkeye]], overpowering Vision by telekinetically burying him hundreds of feet beneath the compound. As expected, Vision is unharmed and later participates in the battle to capture Captain America's allies. He attempts to disable [[Falcon (comics)|Falcon]] but accidentally shoots down and cripples [[War Machine]]. Vision ponders his emotions regarding Scarlet Witch and his desire to ensure her safety, foreshadowing their future relationship.\n** Vision returns in ''[[Avengers: Infinity War]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"CumberbatchInfinity\">{{cite web |url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/714446/Benedict-Cumberbatch-Doctor-Strange-Avengers-3-Infinity-War-Thor-Ragnarok-Robert-Downey-Jr |title=Benedict Cumberbatch\u2019s Doctor Strange CONFIRMED for Avengers: Infinity War |last=Simpson |first=George |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=September 26, 2016 |accessdate=September 26, 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6koPTYPK3?url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/films/714446/Benedict-Cumberbatch-Doctor-Strange-Avengers-3-Infinity-War-Thor-Ragnarok-Robert-Downey-Jr |archivedate=September 26, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"EWBTSPg3\">{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/movies/2018/03/08/avengers-infinity-war-behind-the-scenes/3/ |title=Behind the scenes of Avengers: Infinity War as new heroes unite \u2014 and others will end - page 3 |last=Breznican |first=Anthony |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=March 8, 2018 |accessdate=March 8, 2018 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6xlqwcUGe?url=http://ew.com/movies/2018/03/08/avengers-infinity-war-behind-the-scenes/3/ |archivedate=March 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> At the beginning of the film, he appears in Scotland and is now in a relationship with the fugitive Scarlet Witch while using his powers to make a human disguise. When [[Thanos]]'s army start coming to Earth to take the Mind Stone out of Vision's body, [[Steve Rogers (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Steve Rogers]]'s team take Vision to Wakanda, in the hope that Wakandan science will be able to remove the Mind Stone without killing Vision, so that Scarlet Witch can then destroy the Mind Stone. Unfortunately, Thanos's forces attack Wakanda during the operation, and when Thanos's armies prove too much for even the Avengers and the Wakandan army, Vision convinces Scarlet Witch to destroy the Mind Stone at the cost of his life, confessing his love for her. However, Thanos uses the Time Stone to reverse the Mind Stone's destruction, allowing Thanos to rip the Mind Stone out of Vision's head, killing the android a second time in the process.\n**Vision is briefly featured in the opening sequence of ''[[Spider-Man: Far From Home]]'' (2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/gallery/marvel-easter-eggs-and-references-in-spider-man-fa/2900-2919/2/|title=Marvel Easter Eggs And References In Spider-Man: Far From Home}}</ref> He is one of the four Avengers (alongside Tony Stark, Steve Rogers and [[Natasha Romanoff (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Natasha Romanoff]]) appearing in [[Midtown High School|Midtown High School']]<nowiki/>s video montage which pays homage to all those who died to save Earth.\n\n=== Video games ===\n* Vision is a playable character in the 1991 [[arcade game]] ''[[Captain America and the Avengers]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=7275|title=Captain America And The Avengers|last=|first=|date=|website=The International Arcade Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Vision is a playable character in ''[[Marvel Super Hero Squad Online]].''{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n*Vision is a playable character in the ''[[Marvel Heroes 2015]]'' relaunch.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n* Vision appears as an unlockable character in ''[[Marvel: Avengers Alliance]]''.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n* Vision is a helper/assist character in ''[[Avengers in Galactic Storm]]''.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n* Vision appears as a non-playable character in ''[[Marvel: Ultimate Alliance]]'', voiced by [[Roger Rose]].<ref name=\"btva\"/>\n* Vision appears in ''[[Marvel Heroes (video game)|Marvel Heroes]]'', voiced by [[Dave Wittenberg]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/22231-marvel-heroes-2015-announces-playable-kitty-pryde-blade-x-23-doctor-doom-and-more-for-pre-purchase.html|title=MARVEL HEROES 2015 Announces Playable KITTY PRYDE, BLADE, X-23, DOCTOR DOOM and More for Pre-Purchase|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Vision is a playable character in ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://infinityinquirer.com/|title=Infinity Inquirer \u2013 Your Source For Disney Infinity News|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Vision's original version and [[Marvel Cinematic Universe|MCU]] iteration are playable characters in ''[[Marvel: Contest of Champions]]''.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n* Vision is a playable character in ''[[Marvel: Future Fight]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2015}}\n* Vision is a playable character in ''[[Lego Marvel's Avengers]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/wikis/lego-marvel-avengers/Characters|title=IGN: Lego Marvel's Avengers|last=|first=|date=|website=IGN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> voiced by [[Paul Bettany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0079273/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_0|title=IMDb: Paul Bettany|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Vision appears in ''[[Marvel Avengers Academy]]'', voiced again by JP Karliak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2765391/?ref_=nv_sr_srsg_0|title=IMDb: JP Karliak|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Vision appears as a non-playable character in ''[[Marvel Ultimate Alliance 3: The Black Order]]'', voiced again by David Kaye.<ref name=\"btva\"/> Vision is not one of the combat characters, instead providing valuable intel. After discovering the properties of ISO-8, Vision helps seal Ultron's consciousness within the Mind Stone in order to stop the rogue AI.\n\n=== Books ===\n* \"The Vision\" is the title of a short story by [[Jonathan Lethem]] from his collection ''Men and Cartoons'', in which a character dresses like and claims to be Vision as a child and then continues to dress like the Vision as an adult.\n\n== Collected editions ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" | # \n! width=\"23%\" | Title\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Material collected\n! class=\"unsortable\" width=\"1%\" |Pages\n! width=\"1%\" | Publication date\n! width=\"15%\" |ISBN\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Avengers West Coast: Vision Quest'''\n| ''Avengers West Coast #42-50\n|\n| May 2015\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Avengers: Vision and the Scarlet Witch'''\n| ''Giant-Size Avengers (1974) #4, Vision and Scarlet Witch (1982) #1-4\n|\n| May 2015\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Vision: Yesterday and Tomorrow'''\n| ''Avengers Icons: Vision Vol 1, #1-4, Avengers #57\n|\n| May 2015\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |Volume 2\n|-\n|1\n|'''Little Worse Than A Man'''\n| ''Vision Vol 2 #1-6\n| rowspan=\"2\" |136\n|{{dts|2016-7-12}}\n|{{isbnt|978-0785196570}}\n|-\n|2\n|'''Little Better Than a Beast'''\n| ''Vision Vol 2 #7-12\n|{{dts|2016-12-13}}\n|{{isbnt|978-0785196587}}\n|-\n|1\n|Vision (Vision)\n|Vision Vol 2 ''#1-12''\n|488\n|\n|978-1302908539\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.marvel.com/universe/Vision Vision] at Marvel.com\n* Greg Theakston at Grand Comics Database: [http://comics.org/details.lasso?id=1102#4 ''Marvel Mystery Comics'' #13]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101017134520/http://www.reocities.com/jjnevins/vision.html Jess Nevins' \"Pulp and Adventure Heroes of the Pre-War Years\": The Golden Age Vision]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120822043356/http://www.reocities.com/SunsetStrip/4775/vision.html ''The Invaders'' profile on the Golden Age Vision]\n* [http://www.toonopedia.com/vision2.htm The Vision] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]\n\n{{Mighty Avengers}}\n{{Avengers}}\n{{Avengers characters}}\n{{Stan Lee}}\n\n[[Category:Characters created by John Buscema]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Roy Thomas]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 1968]]\n[[Category:Fictional androids]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with density control abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with energy-manipulation abilities]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can turn intangible]]\n[[Category:Fictional technopaths]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Male characters in film]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics characters with superhuman strength]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics characters who can move at superhuman speeds]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics robots]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics superheroes]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Robot superheroes]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Spelling and typography - Missing end bold/italic)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vision_(Marvel_Comics)"}
{"title_page": "Caldwell First Nation", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Caldwell First Nation\n| official_name                   = Caldwell First Nation Indian Reserve\n| settlement_type                 = [[Indian reserve]]\n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = \n| image_map                       = \n| image_caption                   = Administration building\n| mapsize                         = 200px\n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Canada Ontario\n| pushpin_mapsize                 = 200\n| pushpin_label                   = Caldwell First Nations\n| pushpin_label_position          = left\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|42|03|N|82|35|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{CAN}}\n| subdivision_type1               = Province\n| subdivision_name1               = {{ON}}\n| subdivision_type2               = County\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Essex County, Ontario|Essex]]\n| established_title2              = \n| established_date2               = \n| government_type                 = \n| timezone                        = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = \n| timezone_DST                    = [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal codes in Canada|Postal Code]]\n| postal_code                     = N8H\n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 519 and 226|519 and 226]]\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| leader_title                    = Chief\n| leader_name                     = [[Mary Frances Duckworth]] <ref>http://fnp-ppn.aandc-aadnc.gc.ca/fnp/Main/Search/FNGovernance.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=165&lang=eng</ref>\n| website                         = [http://www.caldwellfirstnation.ca/ www.caldwellfirstnation.ca]\n}}\n\nThe '''Caldwell First Nation'''<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/windsor/caldwell-first-nation-council-chief-conflict-1.4789387</ref> is a [[First Nations]] [[band government]] whose land base is located in [[Leamington, Ontario]],<ref>http://www4.rncan.gc.ca/recherche-de-noms-de-lieux/search?q=+Leamington&category=O</ref> Canada.<ref>https://www.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/DAM/DAM-INTER-HQ-AI/STAGING/texte-text/ai_mprm_fnc_wal_pdf_1344968972421_fra.pdf</ref> They are an [[Anishinaabe]] group, part of the Three Fires Confederacy, comprising the bands [[Potawatomi]], [[Odawa]], and [[Ojibwe|Ojibwa]], whose members are originally of the Mikinaak (Turtle) and the Makwa (Bear) [[dodems]]. The Caldwell First Nation are a distinct and federally recognized Indian band and used to be referred to by such names as the \"Chippewas of Pelee\", \"Point Pelee Indians\" and \"Caldwell's band of Indians.\"\n\nThe Chippewa (also called Ojibwa in [[Canada]]) are an Anishinaabe-speaking indigenous nation with people within the borders of present-day Canada and the [[United States]]. The Anishinaabe are the largest Native American/First Nation peoples north of [[Mexico]], with nearly 78,000 people among various groups in Canada from western [[Quebec]] to [[British Columbia]].\n[[File:Point Pelee National Park looking out at Lake Erie.jpg|thumb|[[Point Pelee]] <ref>[https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/point-pelee-national-park Point Pelee National Park] at [[The Canadian Encyclopedia]], accessed September 3, 2019</ref> is concerned about Caldwell First Nation [[history]].]]\n==History==\nThe Caldwell First Nation, sometimes also called \"the Chippewas of [[Point Pelee]] <ref>http://www4.rncan.gc.ca/recherche-de-noms-de-lieux/search?q=point+pelee&category=O</ref> and [[Pelee Island]] <ref>http://www4.rncan.gc.ca/recherche-de-noms-de-lieux/search?q=pelee+island&category=O</ref>,\" lived as a distinct First Nation in the Point Pelee area from before 1763. Their traditional territory encompassed a broad area corresponding to what is now the [[Ontario]] region, extending from the [[Detroit River]] along [[Amherstburg]] all the way to [[Long Point, Ontario|Long Point]] Ontario and the [[Lake Erie]] Islands. The heart of their ancestral territory includes the Essex and Kent county areas, in particular, the Point Pelee Peninsula and Pelee Island. The Caldwell First Nation considers Point Pelee as \"our home\" and the neighboring Walpole Island First Nation considers Point Pelee as part of \"our house.\"\n\nThe Caldwell First Nation served as allies of the [[United Kingdom|British]] during the [[War of 1812]]. In consideration of this service, they were promised land at Point Pelee. The First Nation continued to occupy Point Pelee, with the support of the Canadian government, up until the late 1850s.<ref name=cbc>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/windsor/caldwell-first-nation-approves-land-claim-offer-1.975428|title=Caldwell First Nation approves land claim offer|website=CBC|date=Aug 23, 2010|accessdate=September 3, 2019}}</ref> In the 1920s, many of the band members were forced out of Point Pelee when the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], along with local law enforcement agencies, burned their homes in the area in an effort to force them from their traditional lands.\n\n==Land claim==\n\nIn May 1790, representatives of certain Ottawa (Odawa), Chippewa (Ojibwa), Pottawatomi (Bod\u00e9wadmi) people and the [[Wyandot people|Huron]] (Wendat) surrendered a large tract of land in southwestern Ontario, including Point Pelee. However, the Caldwell First Nation neither signed nor benefited from that treaty.<ref name=cbc/> The Crown did not realize this and it was publicly acknowledged by the Department of [[Indian and Northern Affairs Canada]]. Caldwell First Nation Council members settled the [[Indigenous specific land claims in Canada|land claim]] that had been outstanding for more than 220 years.\n\nThe Caldwell First Nation is the only federally recognized Indian band in southern Ontario without a [[Indian reserve|reserve]] land of its own.<ref>{{cite book|title=Saskatchewan law review, volume 63|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iKFJAQAAIAAJ|year=2000|page=641|quote=As a result, it was the only federally recognized Indian band in southwestern Ontario without a land base.}}</ref><ref name=cbc/> The Nation is working towards establishing a reserve, which will finally give members the land base.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sharon Hill, The Windsor Star|url=https://windsorstar.com/Caldwells+buying+land/8162778/story.html|title=Caldwells buying land|website=Windsorstar|date=2013-03-28|accessdate=2013-04-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://caldwellfirstnation.ca}}\n*[https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/point-pelee-national-park Caldwell First Nation in Point Pelee National Park], The Canadian Encyclopedia\n*[https://www.britannica.com/place/Canadian-aboriginal-reserves  Caldwell First Nation in Canadian aboriginal reserves article] \u2014 Encyclopedia britannica\n*[http://www.sfns.on.ca/caldwell-first-nation.html Caldwell First Nation] \u2014 Southern First Nations Secretariat (Ontario)\n*[http://fnp-ppn.aandc-aadnc.gc.ca/fnp/Main/Search/FNMain.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=165&lang=eng Caldwell First Nation] \u2014  Indigenous and Northern Affairs Canada\n\n{{Geographic location\n | Centre    = \n | North     = ''[[Lake St.Clair]]''\n | Northeast = \n | East      = [[Lake Erie]]\n | Southeast = \n | South     = [[Lake Erie]]\n | Southwest = \n | West      = ''[[Detroit River]]''\n | Northwest = \n}}\n{{Association of Iroquois and Allied Indians}}\n\n[[Category:First Nations governments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Association of Iroquois and Allied Indians]]\n[[Category:Leamington, Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Caldwell First Nation\n| official_name                   = Caldwell First Nation Indian Reserve\n| settlement_type                 = [[Indian reserve]]\n| nickname                        = \n| motto                           = \n| image_map                       = \n| image_caption                   = Administration building\n| mapsize                         = 200px\n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Canada Ontario\n| pushpin_mapsize                 = 200\n| pushpin_label                   = Caldwell First Nations\n| pushpin_label_position          = left\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|42|03|N|82|35|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{CAN}}\n| subdivision_type1               = Province\n| subdivision_name1               = {{ON}}\n| subdivision_type2               = County\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Essex County, Ontario|Essex]]\n| established_title2              = \n| established_date2               = \n| government_type                 = \n| timezone                        = [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = \n| timezone_DST                    = [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal codes in Canada|Postal Code]]\n| postal_code                     = N8H\n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 519 and 226|519 and 226]]\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| leader_title                    = Chief\n| leader_name                     = [[Mary Frances Duckworth]] <ref>http://fnp-ppn.aandc-aadnc.gc.ca/fnp/Main/Search/FNGovernance.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=165&lang=eng</ref>\n| website                         = [http://www.caldwellfirstnation.ca/ www.caldwellfirstnation.ca]\n}}\n\nThe '''Caldwell First Nation'''<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/windsor/caldwell-first-nation-council-chief-conflict-1.4789387</ref> is a [[First Nations]] [[band government]] whose land base is located in [[Leamington, Ontario]],<ref>http://www4.rncan.gc.ca/recherche-de-noms-de-lieux/search?q=+Leamington&category=O</ref> Canada.<ref>https://www.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/DAM/DAM-INTER-HQ-AI/STAGING/texte-text/ai_mprm_fnc_wal_pdf_1344968972421_fra.pdf</ref> They are an [[Anishinaabe]] group, part of the Three Fires Confederacy, comprising the bands [[Potawatomi]], [[Odawa]], and [[Ojibwe|Ojibwa]], whose members are originally of the Mikinaak (Turtle) and the Makwa (Bear) [[dodems]]. The Caldwell First Nation are a distinct and federally recognized Indian band and used to be referred to by such names as: the \"Chippewas of Pelee\", \"Point Pelee Indians\" and \"Caldwell's band of Indians.\"\n\nThe Chippewa (also called Ojibwa in [[Canada]]) are an Anishinaabe-speaking indigenous nation with people within the borders of present-day Canada and the [[United States]]. The Anishinaabe are the largest Native American/First Nation peoples north of [[Mexico]], with nearly 78,000 people among various groups in Canada from western [[Quebec]] to [[British Columbia]].\n[[File:Point Pelee National Park looking out at Lake Erie.jpg|thumb|[[Point Pelee]] <ref>[https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/point-pelee-national-park Point Pelee National Park] at [[The Canadian Encyclopedia]], accessed September 3, 2019</ref> is concern about Caldwell First Nation [[history]].]]\n==History==\nThe Caldwell First Nation, sometimes also called \"the Chippewas of [[Point Pelee]] <ref>http://www4.rncan.gc.ca/recherche-de-noms-de-lieux/search?q=point+pelee&category=O</ref> and [[Pelee Island]] <ref>http://www4.rncan.gc.ca/recherche-de-noms-de-lieux/search?q=pelee+island&category=O</ref>,\" lived as a distinct First Nation in the Point Pelee area from before 1763. Their traditional territory encompassed a broad area corresponding to what is now the [[Ontario]] region, extending from the [[Detroit River]] along [[Amherstburg]] all the way to [[Long Point, Ontario|Long Point]] Ontario and the [[Lake Erie]] Islands. The heart of their ancestral territory includes the Essex and Kent county areas, in particular the Point Pelee Peninsula and Pelee Island. The Caldwell First Nation considers Point Pelee as \"our home\" and the neighboring Walpole Island First Nation considers Point Pelee as part of \"our house.\"\n\nThe Caldwell First Nation served as allies of the [[United Kingdom|British]] during the [[War of 1812]]. In consideration of this service, they were promised land at Point Pelee. The First Nation continued to occupy Point Pelee, with the support of the Canadian government, up until the late 1850s.<ref name=cbc>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/windsor/caldwell-first-nation-approves-land-claim-offer-1.975428|title=Caldwell First Nation approves land claim offer|website=CBC|date=Aug 23, 2010|accessdate=September 3, 2019}}</ref> In the 1920s, many of the band members were forced out of Point Pelee when the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], along with local law enforcement agencies, burned their homes in the area in an effort to force them from their traditional lands.\n\n==Land claim==\n\nIn May 1790, representatives of certain Ottawa (Odawa), Chippewa (Ojibwa), Pottawatomi (Bod\u00e9wadmi) people and the [[Wyandot people|Huron]] (Wendat) surrendered a large tract of land in southwestern Ontario, including Point Pelee. However, the Caldwell First Nation neither signed nor benefited from that treaty.<ref name=cbc/> The Crown did not realize this and it was publicly acknowledged by the Department of [[Indian and Northern Affairs Canada]]. Caldwell First Nation Council members settled the [[Indigenous specific land claims in Canada|land claim]] that had been outstanding for more than 220 years.\n\nThe Caldwell First Nation is the only federally recognized Indian band in southern Ontario without a [[Indian reserve|reserve]] land of its own.<ref>{{cite book|title=Saskatchewan law review, volume 63|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iKFJAQAAIAAJ|year=2000|page=641|quote=As a result, it was the only federally recognized Indian band in southwestern Ontario without a land base.}}</ref><ref name=cbc/> The Nation is working towards establishing a reserve, which will finally give members the land base.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sharon Hill, The Windsor Star|url=https://windsorstar.com/Caldwells+buying+land/8162778/story.html|title=Caldwells buying land|website=Windsorstar|date=2013-03-28|accessdate=2013-04-25}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://caldwellfirstnation.ca}}\n*[https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/point-pelee-national-park Caldwell First Nation in Point Pelee National Park], The Canadian Encyclopedia\n*[https://www.britannica.com/place/Canadian-aboriginal-reserves  Caldwell First Nation in Canadian aboriginal reserves article] \u2014 Encyclopedia britannica\n*[http://www.sfns.on.ca/caldwell-first-nation.html Caldwell First Nation] \u2014 Southern First Nations Secretariat (Ontario)\n*[http://fnp-ppn.aandc-aadnc.gc.ca/fnp/Main/Search/FNMain.aspx?BAND_NUMBER=165&lang=eng Caldwell First Nation] \u2014  Indigenous and Northern Affairs Canada\n\n{{Geographic location\n | Centre    = \n | North     = ''[[Lake St.Clair]]''\n | Northeast = \n | East      = [[Lake Erie]]\n | Southeast = \n | South     = [[Lake Erie]]\n | Southwest = \n | West      = ''[[Detroit River]]''\n | Northwest = \n}}\n{{Association of Iroquois and Allied Indians}}\n\n[[Category:First Nations governments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Association of Iroquois and Allied Indians]]\n[[Category:Leamington, Ontario]]\n", "name_user": "Lunchtime-Lucas", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor grammatical changes e.g. from \"is concern\" to \"is concerned\", and a comma added following the word particular, and removal of a colon.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caldwell_First_Nation"}
{"title_page": "Sofija Trenchovska", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Sofija Trenchovska\n| image        = Sofija_Trenchovska.jpg\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = 1975\n| birth_place  = [[Strumica]], [[SR Macedonia]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]], nowadays [[North Macedonia]]  \n| education    = {{nowrap|[[Ss. Cyril and Methodius University of Skopje]]}}\n| occupation   = literature, drama, film, Macedonian and Balkan culture\n| years_active = \n| television   = \n| spouse       = [[Goran Trenchovski]]\n| parents      = \n| relatives    = \n}}\n{{Portal|Biography|Literature|Theater|Film|Television|North Macedonia|United Kingdom}}<br />\n'''Sofija Trenchovska''' (also spelled as Tren\u010dovska; {{lang-mk|\u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0422\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0447\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430}}; [[Strumica]], October 9, 1975)  is a writer, editor, producer, philologist and cultural activist from North Macedonia, living in Great Britain.<ref>[http://makedonija.rastko.net/delo/11746 Sofija Trenchovska], Bio\u2013bibliography (Macedonian)</ref> \n\nHer specializations are preserving, digitization and promoting literature. She is the editor\u2013in\u2013chief of the ''Project Rastko \u2014 Macedonia''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160625072016/http://vecer.mk/kultura/besplatni-knigi-na-portalot-rastko \u201cDigitalna biblioteka: besplatni knigi na portalot \u2018Rastko\u2019\u201d], ''Ve\u010der'' daily, 10.3.2008. (Macedonian)</ref>, digital library of Macedonian culture and heritage since 2007.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160924212420/http://www.utrinski.mk/default.asp?ItemID=679E3D5685B2584BBE2B19E7413D16CE \u201cMakedonskata tradicija vo digitalnata biblioteka \u2018Rastko\u2019\u201d], ''Utrinski vesnik'' daily, 17.08.2009. (Macedonian)</ref> \n\n== Biography ==\nShe graduated from the \"[[Bla\u017ee Koneski|Bla\u017ee Koneski]]\" Faculty of Philology \u2014 Department of Macedonian and South Slavic Literature (with general and comparative literature as majors) at the [[Ss. Cyril and Methodius University of Skopje|Ss. Cyril and Methodius University]] in [[Skopje]]. She defended the master's thesis \"Mythopoetics in the early plays of [[Jordan Plevnes|Jordan Plevne\u0161]]\" 2015 at the same Faculty. She completed the School of Doctoral Studies at Ss. Cyril and Methodius University and now she is a PhD candidate with the dissertation in the field of literature and dramaturgy. \n\nFor some time, she worked as a journalist in the daily newspaper ''Ve\u010der'' (Culture section), where she has written lots of articles on education, literature, cinema, theatre and performing arts and as well interviewed artists and cultural workers.\n\nShe was engaged in the several publishing projects. She has been editor\u2013in\u2013chief of the ''Project Rastko \u2014 Macedonia'' (Digital Library of Macedonian Culture and Heritage) since its establishment in 2007.<ref>[https://www.rastko.rs/rastko/delo/14807 \u201cKon 5-godi\u0161niot jubilej na veb-portalot pri Proektot Rastko \u2013 Makedonija\u201d], ''PR-MK'' review, 10.12.2012. (Macedonian)</ref>  Participates in international symposiums and scientific conferences. She researches and writes texts, reviews, studies and essays in periodicals and books.<ref>[https://www.slobodnaevropa.mk/a/27253685.html \u201cPromovirana \u2018Edna mitopoetika\u2019 na Sofija Tren\u010dovska\u201d], ''Radio Free Europe / Radio Liberty'' review, 17.9.2015. (Macedonian)</ref>\n\nTranslates from English, Serbian, Croatian and Bulgarian into Macedonian.\n\n== Works ==\n=== Books ===\n* ''[http://makedonija.rastko.net/cms/files/books/5ac5df51786a4 Edna mitopoetika]'' (A Mythopoetics), Makedonika litera, Skopje, 2015, 164 p. {{ISBN|978-608-4614-94-4}}\n* ''Delo i znak'' (Work and Sign), Makedonika litera, Skopje, 2018, 160 p.\u00a0 {{ISBN|978-608-252-078-0}}\n* ''70 godini posvetenost vo obrazovanieto'' (70 Years Dedicated to Education): Monograph, editor, \"Sofija\", Bogdanci, 2016, 72 p.\u00a0 {{ISBN|978-608-4756-15-6}}\n* ''Narativnite i estetskite vrednosti vo filmot \u2018Zlatna petorka\u2019'' (Narrative and Aesthetic Values of the \u2018Golden Five\u2019 Film): Papers from a Symposium, editor, TFA, 2018, 151 p. {{ISBN|978-608-4546-37-5}}\n* ''15 Rodnokrajci'' (15 Fellow Countrymen) \u2013 poezija i proza od 15 strumi\u010dki avtori: CD Anthology, editor, TFA, 2009. {{ISBN|978-608-4546-00-9}}\n\n=== Papers (choice) ===\n* \u201cKitsch as Art\u201d (\u201eKi\u010dot kako umetnost\u201c), ''Loza'', No. 5, 1997, pp. 9\u201310.\n* \u201cThe Ben Akiba comic mask\u201d (\u201eKomi\u010dnata maska na Ben Akiba\u201c), ''Teatarski glasnik'', No. 47, 1999, pp. 55\u201356.\n* \u201cOn film medium\u201d (\u201eZa filmskiot medium\u201c), ''Akt'', No. 24, 29.10.2007, pp. 50-51.\n* \u201cDemonological beings in Macedonian magic tales\u201d (\u201eDemonolo\u0161kite bitija vo makedonskite vol\u0161ebni prikazni\u201c), ''Akt'', No. 33-34/VI, 31.7.2009, p. 52. \n* \u201cStelar moments in a holy place\u201d (\u201eDzvezdeni migovi na sveto mesto\u201c), ''Premin'', No. 5960/IX, 2009, pp. 58\u201359. \n* \u201cPostmodern disintegration of an imaginary system\u201d (\u201ePostmoderen raspad na eden imaginaren system), ''Akt'', No. 46/IX, 17.8.2012, pp. 42\u201349. \n* \u201c\u2019Erigon\u2019 as the first postmodern play in Macedonia\u201d (\u201e\u2018Erigon\u2019 kako prva postmodernisti\u010dka drama vo Makedonija\u201c), ''Sovremenost'', No. 2/LXV, 2015, pp. 104\u2013107.\n* \u201cChernodrinski\u2019s \u2018Slav Dragota\u2019 and the reasons of Belasica\u2019s defeat\u201d (\u201eSlav Dragota na \u010cernodrinski i pri\u010dinite za porazot na Belasica\u201c) in: ''Samuilovata dr\u017eava vo istoriskata, voeno\u2013politi\u010dkata, duhovnata i kulturnata tradicija na Makedonija'', Papers from a Symposium, NI Institute and Museum Strumica, 2015, pp. 298\u2013304. \n* \u201cFocalisation in the Abad\u017eiev\u2019s \u2018Tobacco Case\u2019\u201d (\u201eFokalizacijata vo \u2018Tabakerata\u2019 na Abad\u017eiev\u201c), ''Mediantrop'', No. 10\u201311/IV, May\u2013June 2015, https://www.mediantrop.rankomunitic.org/2015-05-30-18-01-33\n* \u201cFaith and Art: narrative and aesthetic values of the \u2018Golden Five\u2019 film\u201d (\u201eVerata i umetnosta: narativnite i estetskite vrednosti vo filmot \u2018Zlatna petorka\u2019\u201c), ''Premin'', No. 127\u2013128/ XVIII, 2018, pp. 74\u201375.\n* \u201cCreative reflections in Ibzen and Vapcarov drama poetics\u201d (\u201eKreativnite refleksii vo dramskite poetiki na Ibzen i Vapcarov\u201c), ''Makedonika'', No. 19\u201320/VIII, 2018, pp. 64\u201372.\n* \u201cCarnivalistic instead humanistic sensation of the world\u201d (\u201eKarnevalisti\u010dkoto nasproti humanisti\u010dkoto do\u017eivuvanje na svetot\u201c), ''Conference proceedings, FILKO, Third International Scientific Conference'', \"Goce Del\u010dev\" University in \u0160tip, 26-27 April 2018, pp. 673-680, http://js.ugd.edu.mk/index.php/fe/article/view/2720\n\n=== Translations (choice) ===\n* [[Du\u0161an Kova\u010devi\u0107]], \"Larry Thompson\", a play staged at the National Theatre \u2013 \u0160tip, 2001/2002 repertory season.\n* [[Radomir Konstantinovi\u0107]], \"Beckett the Friend\" (\"Beket, prijatelot\" / \"Beket prijatelj\"), ''Akt'', no. 30, 26.12.2008, pp. 53\u201357.\n* [[Boro Dra\u0161kovi\u0107]], ''Director's Notes'', with G. Trenchovski, N. Sarajlija, A. Gogov, TFA, Strumica, 2012.\n* [[Zoran Stefanovi\u0107]], ''Slavic Orpheus'', with G. Trenchovski, TFA, Strumica, 2014.\n\n=== Producer, organizer (choice) ===\n* 2005 \u2013 till now \u2013 Co\u2013organizer of the AsterFest International Film Festival and of the events organized by the Tiberiopolian Film Alliance.\n* 2007 \u2013 Producer of the ''Martin from the Stairs'', live action TV series for children (six episodes). \n* 2013 \u2013 Children coordinator of the ''Play & Save'', short live action film. \n* 2015 \u2013 Children coordinator of the ''Golden Five'' feature live action film and of the ''Love and Betrayal'' live action TV series (five episodes). \n* 2018 \u2013 Coordinator of the international scholar project \"Narrative and aesthetic values \u200b\u200bin the film 'Golden Five'\".\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMDb name|id=4736037}}\n* [http://makedonija.rastko.net/ Project Rastko \u2014 Macedonia], digital library of Macedonian culture and heritage (Macedonian; also some works: English, Serbian, Albanian etc)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trenchovska, Sofija}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:People from Strumica]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Macedonian film producers]]\n[[Category:Macedonian women writers]]\n[[Category:Literary critics]]\n[[Category:Literary historians]]\n[[Category:Philologists]]\n[[Category:Macedonian journalists]]\n[[Category:Macedonian translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century Macedonian writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Macedonian writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Sofija Trenchovska\n| image        = Sofija_Trenchovska.jpg\n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = 1975\n| birth_place  = [[Strumica]], [[SR Macedonia]], [[SFR Yugoslavia]], nowadays [[North Macedonia]]  \n| education    = {{nowrap|[[Ss. Cyril and Methodius University of Skopje]]}}\n| occupation   = literature, drama, film, Macedonian and Balkan culture\n| years_active = \n| television   = \n| spouse       = [[Goran Trenchovski]]\n| parents      = \n| relatives    = \n}}\n{{Portal|Biography|Literature|Theater|Film|Television|North Macedonia|United Kingdom}}<br />\n'''Sofija Trenchovska''' (also spelled as Tren\u010dovska; {{lang-mk|\u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0422\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0447\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430}}; [[Strumica]], October 9, 1975)  is a writer, editor, producer, philologist and cultural activist from North Macedonia, living in Great Britain.<ref>[http://makedonija.rastko.net/delo/11746 Sofija Trenchovska], Bio\u2013bibliography (Macedonian)</ref> \n\nHer specializations are preserving, digitization and promoting literature. She is the editor\u2013in\u2013chief of the ''Project Rastko \u2014 Macedonia''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160625072016/http://vecer.mk/kultura/besplatni-knigi-na-portalot-rastko \u201cDigitalna biblioteka: besplatni knigi na portalot \u2018Rastko\u2019\u201d], ''Ve\u010der'' daily, 10.3.2008. (Macedonian)</ref>, digital library of Macedonian culture and heritage since 2007.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160924212420/http://www.utrinski.mk/default.asp?ItemID=679E3D5685B2584BBE2B19E7413D16CE \u201cMakedonskata tradicija vo digitalnata biblioteka \u2018Rastko\u2019\u201d], ''Utrinski vesnik'' daily, 17.08.2009. (Macedonian)</ref> \n\n== Biography ==\nShe graduated from the \"[[Bla\u017ee Koneski|Bla\u017ee Koneski]]\" Faculty of Philology \u2014 Department of Macedonian and South Slavic Literature (with general and comparative literature as majors) at the [[Ss. Cyril and Methodius University of Skopje|Ss. Cyril and Methodius University]] in [[Skopje]]. She defended the master's thesis \"Mythopoetics in the early plays of [[Jordan Plevnes|Jordan Plevne\u0161]]\" 2015 at the same Faculty. She completed the School of Doctoral Studies at Ss. Cyril and Methodius University and now she is a PhD candidate with the dissertation in the field of literature and dramaturgy. \n\nFor some time, she worked as a journalist in the daily newspaper ''Ve\u010der'' (Culture section), where she has written lots of articles on education, literature, cinema, theatre and performing arts and as well interviewed artists and cultural workers.\n\nShe was engaged in the several publishing projects. She has been editor\u2013in\u2013chief of the ''Project Rastko \u2014 Macedonia'' (Digital Library of Macedonian Culture and Heritage) since its establishment in 2007.<ref>[https://www.rastko.rs/rastko/delo/14807 \u201cKon 5-godi\u0161niot jubilej na veb-portalot pri Proektot Rastko \u2013 Makedonija\u201d], ''PR-MK'' review, 10.12.2012. (Macedonian)</ref>  Participates in international symposiums and scientific conferences. She researches and writes texts, reviews, studies and essays in periodicals and books.<ref>[https://www.slobodnaevropa.mk/a/27253685.html \u201cPromovirana \u2018Edna mitopoetika\u2019 na Sofija Tren\u010dovska\u201d], ''Radio Free Europe / Radio Liberty'' review, 17.9.2015. (Macedonian)</ref>\n\nTranslates from English, Serbian, Croatian and Bulgarian into Macedonian.\n\n== Works ==\n=== Books ===\n* ''[http://makedonija.rastko.net/cms/files/books/5ac5df51786a4 Edna mitopoetika]'' (A Mythopoetics), Makedonika litera, Skopje, 2015, 164 p. {{ISBN|978-608-4614-94-4}}\n* ''Delo i znak'' (Work and Sign), Makedonika litera, Skopje, 2018, 160 p.\u00a0 {{ISBN|978-608-252-078-0}}\n* ''70 godini posvetenost vo obrazovanieto'' (70 Years Dedicated to Education): Monograph, editor, \"Sofija\", Bogdanci, 2016, 72 p.\u00a0 {{ISBN|978-608-4756-15-6}}\n* ''Narativnite i estetskite vrednosti vo filmot \u2018Zlatna petorka\u2019'' (Narrative and Aesthetic Values of the \u2018Golden Five\u2019 Film): Papers from a Symposium, editor, TFA, 2018, 151 p. {{ISBN|978-608-4546-37-5}}\n* ''15 Rodnokrajci'' (15 Fellow Countrymen) \u2013 poezija i proza od 15 strumi\u010dki avtori: CD Anthology, editor, TFA, 2009. {{ISBN|978-608-4546-00-9}}\n\n=== Papers (choice) ===\n* \u201cKitsch as Art\u201d (\u201eKi\u010dot kako umetnost\u201c), ''Loza'', No. 5, 1997, pp. 9\u201310.\n* \u201cThe Ben Akiba comic mask\u201d (\u201eKomi\u010dnata maska na Ben Akiba\u201c), ''Teatarski glasnik'', No. 47, 1999, pp. 55\u201356.\n* \u201cOn film medium\u201d (\u201eZa filmskiot medium\u201c), ''Akt'', No. 24, 29.10.2007, pp. 50-51.\n* \u201cDemonological beings in Macedonian magic tales\u201d (\u201eDemonolo\u0161kite bitija vo makedonskite vol\u0161ebni prikazni\u201c), ''Akt'', No. 33-34/VI, 31.7.2009, p. 52. \n* \u201cStar moments in a holy place\u201d (\u201eDzvezdeni migovi na sveto mesto\u201c), ''Premin'', No. 5960/IX, 2009, pp. 58\u201359. \n* \u201cPostmodern disintegration of an imaginary system\u201d (\u201ePostmoderen raspad na eden imaginaren system), ''Akt'', No. 46/IX, 17.8.2012, pp. 42\u201349. \n* \u201c\u2019Erigon\u2019 as the first postmodern play in Macedonia\u201d (\u201e\u2018Erigon\u2019 kako prva postmodernisti\u010dka drama vo Makedonija\u201c), ''Sovremenost'', No. 2/LXV, 2015, pp. 104\u2013107.\n* \u201cChernodrinski\u2019s \u2018Slav Dragota\u2019 and the reasons of Belasica\u2019s defeat\u201d (\u201eSlav Dragota na \u010cernodrinski i pri\u010dinite za porazot na Belasica\u201c) in: ''Samuilovata dr\u017eava vo istoriskata, voeno\u2013politi\u010dkata, duhovnata i kulturnata tradicija na Makedonija'', Papers from a Symposium, NI Institute and Museum Strumica, 2015, pp. 298\u2013304. \n* \u201cFocalisation in the Abad\u017eiev\u2019s \u2018Tobacco Case\u2019\u201d (\u201eFokalizacijata vo \u2018Tabakerata\u2019 na Abad\u017eiev\u201c), ''Mediantrop'', No. 10\u201311/IV, May\u2013June 2015, https://www.mediantrop.rankomunitic.org/2015-05-30-18-01-33\n* \u201cFaith and Art: narrative and aesthetic values of the \u2018Golden Five\u2019 film\u201d (\u201eVerata i umetnosta: narativnite i estetskite vrednosti vo filmot \u2018Zlatna petorka\u2019\u201c), ''Premin'', No. 127\u2013128/ XVIII, 2018, pp. 74\u201375.\n* \u201cCreative reflections in Ibzen and Vapcarov drama poetics\u201d (\u201eKreativnite refleksii vo dramskite poetiki na Ibzen i Vapcarov\u201c), ''Makedonika'', No. 19\u201320/VIII, 2018, pp. 64\u201372.\n* \u201cCarnivalistic instead humanistic sensation of the world\u201d (\u201eKarnevalisti\u010dkoto nasproti humanisti\u010dkoto do\u017eivuvanje na svetot\u201c), ''Conference proceedings, FILKO, Third International Scientific Conference'', \"Goce Del\u010dev\" University in \u0160tip, 26-27 April 2018, pp. 673-680, http://js.ugd.edu.mk/index.php/fe/article/view/2720\n\n=== Translations (choice) ===\n* [[Du\u0161an Kova\u010devi\u0107]], \"Larry Thompson\", a play staged at the National Theatre \u2013 \u0160tip, 2001/2002 repertory season.\n* [[Radomir Konstantinovi\u0107]], \"Beckett the Friend\" (\"Beket, prijatelot\" / \"Beket prijatelj\"), ''Akt'', no. 30, 26.12.2008, pp. 53\u201357.\n* [[Boro Dra\u0161kovi\u0107]], ''Director's Notes'', with G. Trenchovski, N. Sarajlija, A. Gogov, TFA, Strumica, 2012.\n* [[Zoran Stefanovi\u0107]], ''Slavic Orpheus'', with G. Trenchovski, TFA, Strumica, 2014.\n\n=== Producer, organizer (choice) ===\n* 2005 \u2013 till now \u2013 Co\u2013organizer of the AsterFest International Film Festival and of the events organized by the Tiberiopolian Film Alliance.\n* 2007 \u2013 Producer of the ''Martin from the Stairs'', live action TV series for children (six episodes). \n* 2013 \u2013 Children coordinator of the ''Play & Save'', short live action film. \n* 2015 \u2013 Children coordinator of the ''Golden Five'' feature live action film and of the ''Love and Betrayal'' live action TV series (five episodes). \n* 2018 \u2013 Coordinator of the international scholar project \"Narrative and aesthetic values \u200b\u200bin the film 'Golden Five'\".\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{IMDb name|id=4736037}}\n* [http://makedonija.rastko.net/ Project Rastko \u2014 Macedonia], digital library of Macedonian culture and heritage (Macedonian; also some works: English, Serbian, Albanian etc)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trenchovska, Sofija}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:People from Strumica]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Macedonian film producers]]\n[[Category:Macedonian women writers]]\n[[Category:Literary critics]]\n[[Category:Literary historians]]\n[[Category:Philologists]]\n[[Category:Macedonian journalists]]\n[[Category:Macedonian translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century Macedonian writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Macedonian writers]]\n", "name_user": "Rastko-mk",